<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Reaches Final by Beating Netherlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BRUSSELS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Italy will meet France in the
Euro 2000
final by beating co-hosts the Netherlands 3-1 in a penalty
shootout following a 0-0 draw after extra time in Amsterdam, the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The final will be held in Rotterdam Sunday when the Italians
meet the world champion, who beat Portugal 2-1 thanks to Zinedine
Zidane's "golden goal" penalty in Brussels Wednesday, for the
first time in the tournament final since 1968.
</P>
<P>
Italy won after their goalkeeper Francesco Toldo saved two of
the penalty shootout from Dutch captain Frank de Boer and Paul
Bosvelt. Jaap Stam blazed one over the bar.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch had missed two penalties in normal time with the
Italians down to 10 men for most of the match after midfielder
Ginaluca Zambrotta was sent off in the 33rd minute for a second
yellow card.
</P>
<P>
Toldo saved De Boer's earlier spot kick and Patrick Kluivert
hit a post, also in normal time.
</P>
<P>
It was a massive disappointment for the 50,000 crowd in the
Amsterdam Arena who saw the Italians defend solidly for long
periods after Zambrotta was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
The pattern of the match had been established from the first
whistle with Italy content to sit deep, soak up pressure and hope
to hit on the counter.
</P>
<P>
But they looked shaky at the back and Dennis Bergkamp, who
sent a header wide when unmarked in the 12th minute, ghosted past
Mark Iuliano before smacking a low shot against a post three
minutes later.
</P>
<P>
Italy, with Alessandro Del Piero preferred in the starting
lineup to Francesco Totti, rarely escaped from their own half and
then suffered a huge blow when Zambrotta was given his second
yellow card in the 33rd minute.
</P>
<P>
"In the first half we had them on the ropes. And then I miss a
penalty," De Boer said. "Later we just didn't have the patience.
</P>
<P>
"In the shootout, they had the psychologicial advantage
because we had already missed two. We missed five penalties. It's
very sad. We cannot finish our job. We had a great chance to win
the championship and we only have ourselves to blame."
</P>
<P>
Coach Frank Rijkaard said penalty misses by De Boer and
Kluivert during normal time cost them a place in the final for the
first time since 1988.
</P>
<P>
"The (missed) penalties were crucial," he said. "If one would
have gone in it would have meant we were 1-0 against ten men.
</P>
<P>
"We just could not force a breakthrough. The end just wore us
down. It took too much out of us. It was our mistake that we could
not bring down this defensive wall.
</P>
<P>
"Two penalties and we miss them both," Rijkaard said. "We
practiced penalties almost every day and now it is clear we are
not strong enough.
</P>
<P>
"All this is disastrous. This is such a missed opportunity.
This will take a long time to heal.''
</P>
<P>
Italian coach Dino Zoff sprang a surprise by naming Alessandro
Del Piero as a starter and relegating Francesco Totti to the bench.
Totti was brought into the game late on for Stefano Fiore.
</P>
<P>
Struggling to contain the Dutch midfielders, Italy's Zambrotta
and Mark Iuliano were shown the yellow card within two minutes of
each other for hauling down Boudewijn Zenden and Mark Overmars a
long way from the Italian goal with little danger to Toldo.
</P>
<P>
Zenden became the third player to be shown the yellow card
when he was challenged by Alessandro Nesta just inside the area on
the left but went down without any contact and was cautioned for
diving.
</P>
<P>
When Zenden went down again in the 33rd minute by Zambrotta
and the Italian was sent off for his second yellow card.
</P>
<P>
Five minutes later the Dutch were awarded the penalty when
Kluivert had his shirt pulled by Nesta. But Toldo guessed right
and dived to his left to block De Boer's firmly struck spot kick
and the shorthanded Italians remained level.
</P>
<P>
Just before half time Kluivert moved into a shooting chance
but pulled his shot across the face of the goal.
</P>
<P>
With the Italians losing their cool, Toldo and Maldini also
were shown the yellow card during the first half by German referee
Markus Merk.
</P>
<P>
Dutch goalkeeper Van de Sar made his first save of the game in
the third minute of the second half and didn't even need to. Fiore
's shot was sailing well wide of the post but the keeper flung
himself to his right to palm the ball away at the expense of a
corner which, fortunately for him, came to nothing.
</P>
<P>
At the other end, Zenden ended a slick Dutch move with a
powerful left footed volley which was straight at Toldo before the
Italians handed the host another chance from the penalty spot.
</P>
<P>
Edgar Davids clearly had Iuliano beaten for speed when the
Italian defender stuck out a foot and upended his Juventus
colleague just inside the area. This time Kluivert stepped up to
take the spot kick and, although Toldo dived the wrong way, he hit
the post. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
