<HEADLINE> Vietnam-U.S. Trade Agreement Should Benefit Both Countries, Says Vietnamese Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Trade Minister Vu Khoan
said that Vietnam-U.S. bilateral trade agreement (BTA) should
benefit both the United States and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Khoan made the remarks when he granted an exclusive interview
here to Vietnam News Agency on Thursday on his coming visit to
Washington as guest of U.S. Trade Representative Charlene
Barshefsky.
</P>
<P>
Khoan said his visit to Washington aims to work with Barshefsky
and her colleagues to compare notes on the completion of BTA
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that "the process of relation normalization between
Vietnam and the United States officially commenced five years ago.
Both sides are of the same view that it is necessary to reach a
BTA to cover the whole process. After more than four years of
negotiations, which was far from simple, the two countries arrived
at an agreement in principle on the BTA last year. However, there
remained some issues to be clarified so the BTA was not signed at
that time."
</P>
<P>
"Any international agreement must show a balance in terms of
interest and must be acceptable to both sides. In other words, it
should reflect the principles of equality and mutual benefit," the
Vietnamese trade minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover it will benefit cooperation in the Asia-Pacific
Region and Southeast Asia. I hope the United States share the same
view. Once both sides work on this with great interest, they will
be able to find solutions satisfactory for settling outstanding
issues and will arrive at the agreement," Khoan added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
