<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Lower House Passes 2001 Budget Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 29 (Xinhua) -- After two days' deliberation and
amid the pressure of members' resignation, The House of
Representatives of Thailand, the lower house of the parliament,
eventually passed the 2001 budget bill midnight Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 910-billion-baht (23.24 billion U.S. dollars) budget bill,
for the fiscal year starting from October, was passed with 202
affirmative votes, 2 opposing votes and 4 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai has tried to convince the House
members that the passage of the 2001 budget bill prior to the
House dissolution is significant for the smooth recovery of the
Thai economy.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda also reiterated that
the passage of the budget bill was crucial for the economy, saying
the delayed implementation of the budget bill would cause serious
negative effects to continued recovering processes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has called for the opposition House
members to realize and maintain their political responsibilities
for the sake of the public and national interests.
</P>
<P>
Attempting to force a dissolution of the House, fifty House
members of the New Aspiration Party (NAP), the leader of the
opposition, resigned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Another forty-three House members belonging to the defected
Wang Nam Yen faction of the NAP has submitted their resignation,
which will be effective since Friday.
</P>
<P>
Three more NAP House members are also set to resign Friday.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the forty-five opposition House members, including
nineteen from the Social Action Party (SAP), though not resigning,
have called for the government to withdraw the deliberation of the
budget bill from the House agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
