<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Sanctions Against Austria Remain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Portuguese government said
Thursday that the 14 partners of Austria in the European Union are
not yet lifting their sanctions against the country, imposed at
the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Portugal, now holds the EU's rotating presidency, was meanwhile
mandated to ask the France-based European Court of Human Rights to
monitor whether Austria is abiding by "common European values,"
which cover "the rights of minorities, refugees and immigrants."
The court will also monitor "the evolution of the political nature
" of the far-right Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
The court will appoint three people to do an investigation and
report their finding to the 14 governments. Those states will
decide whether to lift the diplomatic sanctions after considering
the reports.
</P>
<P>
The punitive measures were imposed in February after the
Freedom Party joined Austria's coalition government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
