<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian President Concerned Over Adoption of Islamic Law in Northern State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
expressed concern over the decision of the most populous northern
State Kano to adopt Sharia Islamic law.
</P>
<P>
President Olusegun Obasanjo has sent his special adviser
Alphonsus Nwosu to the state to express his worries, reports
reaching here from the country's capital Abuja said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nwosu told Kano State Governor Rabiu Kwankwaso that Obasanjo
was alarmed by his June 21 declaration of plans to introduce
Sharia, which includes punishments such as amputation and
flogging.
</P>
<P>
The president said he would be very brutal in his second year
in office with anyone who takes him for granted, by mistaking his
calmness for weakness, according to Nwosu.
</P>
<P>
The Kano governor replied that the declaration last week would
not be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
"Tell the president that Sharia is in the interest of the state
and Nigeria. Sharia is irrevocable and we are not ready to
surrender our constitutional right to anybody," Kwankwaso said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Kano became the third state in the mainly Muslim
north Nigeria to adopt Sharia, despite strong opposition from
northern Christians.
</P>
<P>
There are fears that Kano's move could revive the sectarian
violence in which over 1,000 have died in Nigeria this year.
</P>
<P>
Since October last year, four northern states, including
Zamfara, Niger, Sokoto, and Kano, have declared to adopt Islamic
law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
