<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Distressed by Sunk Boat in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- U.N.Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Friday was distressed by the news that an overcrowded
boat carrying persons fleeing the clashes in northern Maluku
Province of Indonesia and bound for North Sulawesi had sunk during
a violent storm.
</P>
<P>
Annan expressed his condolences to the Government of Indonesia
and to the families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General voiced his concern over the escalation of
violence in the Maluku and North Maluku provinces and the steady
deterioration in the humanitarian situation, and the related
reports of large numbers of people killed and widespread
displacement of population.
</P>
<P>
Annan appealed to those perpetrating this violence to respect
humanitarian law and principles and to ensure the protection of
civilians.
</P>
<P>
Annan said they must allow safe and unimpeded access to enable
humanitarian workers to provide assistance to the populations in
need.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated ferry disappeared while on a voyage of more than
200 miles to Manado in Sulawesi from the Malukus, a corner of the
Indonesian archipelago where violence between Muslims and
Christians has killed almost 3,000 people of both faiths in the
past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
After more than 30 hours of searching by air and sea, Indonesia
's military and private craft was unable to find any trace of the
ship that sank Thursday with almost 500 people on board. Most of
them are refugees fleeing the violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
