<HEADLINE> FAO Head in Iraq on Fact-finding Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Director General of the United
Nations Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO), Jacques Diouf,
arrived here Friday on a fact-finding visit.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to focus on the tragic accident that two staffers
of the FAO office in Baghdad were killed by a gunman early
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The gunman, identified as 38-year-old Fuad Haidar, shot and
killed the two FAO staffers -- a Somali and an Iraqi -- with the
claimed aim to protest the decade-old U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Several others were injured as well. Haidar surrendered to the
authorities after a two-hour confrontation with Iraqi security
forces.
</P>
<P>
The crippling U.N. sanctions, imposed since Iraq's 1990 invasion
of Kuwait, have been blamed for hundreds of thousands of deaths in
Iraq because of lack of food, medicine and other humanitarian
supplies. 
</P>
