<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Embassy Cancels National Day Celebration in Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. embassy in Amman has decided
to cancel its Independence Day celebration for security concern,
despite Jordanian efforts to play down terrorist threats against U.
S. targets in the kingdom, diplomatic sources here said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The July 4 celebration used to be held each year at the U.S.
ambassador's residence in Amman and attended by hundreds of
Jordanian dignitaries and representatives from the diplomatic
corps.
</P>
<P>
U.S. diplomats described the cancellation as part of increased
security measures for the embassy compound after the embassy warned
a week ago on its Internet website of "terrorist targeting" of the
embassy and other American targets in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The mission also advised American citizens travelling in the
kingdom to keep low profile and take extra prudence.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian officials had played down the U.S. warning and
described it as "routine alerts" issued by U.S. embassies in most
regions of the world, saying there was nothing new in terms of
threats to justify such a statement in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
However, after the warning, Jordanian security forces have
apparently beefed up security of the already heavily guarded U.S.
embassy in the affluent Abdoun area in southern Amman.
</P>
<P>
Similar warnings were issued by the U.S. government and the U.S.
embassy in Amman last December, when Jordanian police rounded up 14
suspected terrorists who allegedly sneaked into the kingdom on
forged travel documents to sabotage the new millenium celebrations.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution said the suspects, believed to be linked to the
Afghanistan-based Saudi-expelled billionaire Osama bin Laden, had
planned attacks on American and Israeli targets during the New Year
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Bin Laden is one of the most wanted suspects by Washington,
which accused him of masterminding the 1998 bombings of the U.S.
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, killing over 200 people.
</P>
<P>
However, no serious attacks on American targets were reported in
Jordan in recent memory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
