<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Anti-Discrimination Committee Ends Twenty-Third Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Committee on the
Elimination of Discrimination against Women(CEDAW) on Friday
concluded its twenty-third session at the Headquarters of the
United Nations in New York.
</P>
<P>
The Committee, the only United Nations human rights treaty body
that deals exclusively with women's rights, began the present
session on June 12.
</P>
<P>
The Committee considered reports from seven States Parties to
the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination
against Women, Austria, Cameroon, Cuba, Iraq, Lithuania, Moldova
and Romania.
</P>
<P>
In their reports, Cuba and Iraq cited embargoes and sanctions
as impediment to advancement and the full implementation of the
Convention.
</P>
<P>
Lithuania, Moldova and Romania, as economies in transition,
experienced economic upheaval and hardship, resulting in high
unemployment and poverty among women.
</P>
<P>
Cameroon showed commitment to improving the status of women,
through the adoption of a national plan against female genital
mutilation seeking to improve health and living conditions of
women and to put an end to the practice.
</P>
<P>
Austria, a country of destination for women victims of
trafficking, was committed to combating the problem, by
establishing a victim protection facility for psychological,
health, legal and family matters, and to facilitate women's return
and employment in the source countries.
</P>
<P>
CEDAW's twenty-third session is particularly noteworthy as it
came immediately after the recently ended Beijing+5 General
Assembly Special Session on women held from June 5 to 9, which
made several recommendations of particular value to the work of
CEDAW and which intensify the strength of the Convention. The
outcome document also addressed many of the concerns raised by the
Committee with regard to countries under review.
</P>
<P>
Since 1997, the Committee has met twice annually. To date, the
Committee has considered 105 initial, 75 second, 51 third and 15
fourth periodic reports.
</P>
<P>
The Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of
Discrimination against Women was adopted by the General Assembly
in December 1979, and rapid ratification brought it into force on
September 1981. To date, 165 countries have become parties to the
Convention.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sunderland Nissan's Future In Doubt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The UK car industry is in trouble
again, after a threat by Nissan to shift production from its
Sunderland plant to the continent because of the strength of
sterling.
</P>
<P>
Sunderland Nissan in England is Europe's most productive car
factory, with 5000 workers producing about 330,000 cars a year.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Ghosn, the Nissan president told the Financial Times
Friday that the strength of sterling could jeopardize a potential
150 million pounds expansion.
</P>
<P>
Production could drop by as much as 50 percent if it fails to
win its bid to build the new Micra model, Ghosn added.
</P>
<P>
A number of other car firms - Toyota, Honda, BMW and General
Motors (Vauxhall) - have already expressed their unease about the
value of the pound, and warned that uncertainty about British
membership of the euro could affect their investment decisions.
</P>
<P>
Ghosn said Nissan had no intention of closing the plant, but
would decide by the end of the year whether to build its next
generation of Micras there.
</P>
<P>
It is believed here Nissan's warnings are bound to fuel the
debate in the UK, and especially British industry,over euro
membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
