government and the main rebel group, the Sudan People's Liberation
Army (SPLA).
</P>
<P>
The peaceful resolution of the Sudanese civil war would help
bring about a lasting peace and stability in the Horn of Africa,
the president was quoted by a spokesperson of the Ministry of
Foreign Affairs as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia remains committed to back up the Inter-Governmental
Authority on Development (IGAD) peace initiatives designed to
bring the Sudanese government and the SPLA to the negotiating
table, he said, when conferring with a delegation of the IGAD
sub-committee on the problem in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The president also stressed the need to exert an all-out effort
to avert series of conflicts and the impacts of periodical drought
in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesperson, the IGAD delegation headed by
Executive Secretary Atallaha Mohammed, told Jidada that a series
of talks were held on the Declaration of Principles between the
Sudanese government and the SPLA in January, February and April
this year.
</P>
<P>
The Declaration of Principles, proposed by the IGAD in 1994,
calls for the separation of religion from politics, the
establishment of a secular country and a referendum over the
future political system in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Significant achievement has been made during the talks, which
centered on the substantive issues of state and the religion,
Mohammed said.
</P>
<P>
However, the IGAD official also noted that much is yet to be
done to achieve a full- fledged consensus between the two warring
parties of Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Military conflicts between the Sudanese government and the SPLA
have been going on since 1983 due to sharp differences over the
practice of Islamic law in southern Sudan. 
</P>
