<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Findings Might Lead to Ways of Treating Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have found a way for
the first time to make fruit fly carry malaria and infect chickens
with the deadly disease, paving the way to better fight malarial.
</P>
<P>
The new finding was reported in Friday's Science journal.
</P>
<P>
Malaria remains one of the most devastating public health
menaces in the world today, killing more than one million people a
year.
</P>
<P>
However, scientists know very little about how mosquitoes carry
malaria and transmit it from person to person, largely because the
insects are difficult to manipulate and not conducive to
laboratory studies.
</P>
<P>
Along with scientists with the National Institute of Allergy
and Infectious Disease, David Schneider, a fellow at the Whitehead
Institute and the leading author of the study, turned to fruit
flies, an excellent model to study human diseases.
</P>
<P>
Schneider injected a form of Plasmodium, the parasite that
causes malaria in chickens, into the body cavity of the flies.
When he allowed the carrier flies to infect chickens, the birds
developed full-blown malaria.
</P>
<P>
He also observed that a component of the fly's immune system,
known as a macrophage, was able to destroy Plasmodia in an attempt
to fight the infection. Theses results suggest that the fruit fly
can indeed serve as a model for studying malaria parasite.
</P>
<P>
"One advantage of using fruit flies instead of mosquitoes is
that we can do large-scale genetic screens to find mutants," says
Schneider, "We can knock out genes to determine whether the
parasites grow better or worse when a particular gene is missing."
</P>
<P>
Because parts of the human immune system are very similar to
those of fruit flies, this approach will hopefully lead to new
ways to treat malaria.
</P>
<P>
"The first drugs to treat malaria were inexpensive and had few
side effects, but they are no longer effective because the
parasite has become resistant," Schneider explains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
