<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Americans' Income, Spending Up in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Americans' incomes increased 0.
4 percent in May, and their consumption spending rose 0.2 percent,
the Commerce Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
It was the second month in a row in which personal incomes rose
faster than spending, suggesting that Americans' less frenzied
pace of spending may help to slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
In April, Americans' incomes, which include wages, interest and
government benefits, rose 0.6 percent, a little slower than the
government previously thought. Consumer spending grew by 0.2
percent, half as fast as the government estimated one month ago.
</P>
<P>
Disposable personal income, or income less personal tax
payments, increased 0.4 percent in May compared with a 0.5 percent
rise in the month before.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the personal savings rate, savings as a percentage
of after-tax income, rose to 0.6 percent in May from 0.4 percent
the month before. Last month's rate was the highest since 0.8
percent in January.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending has been the engine of the robust U.S.
economy and accounts for two-thirds of all economic activities.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has boosted interest rates six times in the
last 12 months to slow the economy and keep inflation under
control. The Fed's rate increases are designed to make borrowing
more expensive and cool demand for such big-ticket items as cars
and homes.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Fed, citing tentative signs of slowing,
decided not to raise rates for a seventh time but left the door
open to further rate increases should inflation worsen.
</P>
<P>
Friday's report also showed that Americans' spending on durable
goods, cars and other big-ticket manufactured goods expected to
last at least three years, fell 1 percent in May. That followed a
0.7 percent drop the month before.
</P>
<P>
Spending on nondurable goods, such as food and fuel, rose 0.2
percent after a 0.2 percent decline in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
