<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets on Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Friday continued its closed-door discussion on the latest
developments in Sierra Leone, where 234 U.N. peacekeepers and
military observers are still being surrounded by rebels in the
West African country.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came after U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
welcomed the news that 21 U.N. peacekeepers were freed by the
rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) with the assistance of
Liberian President Charles Taylor.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who has been in contact with President Taylor regarding
the detained peacekeepers, was hopeful that "this welcome step
will be followed by the immediate and unconditional freedom of
movement of the UNAMSIL (the U.N. Mission in Sierra Leone)
personnel who still remain surrounded by the RUF in the area of
Kailahun," a U.N. statement said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The released U.N. peacekeepers, all Indian nationals, were
already in the Liberian capital of Monrovia and expected to be
flown later to Freetown, the capital of Sierra Leone, said Taylor
in a statement released from Monrovia by the Information Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The rebels were detaining the Indian peacekeepers in Pendembu
near the Liberian border, and are still surrounding 222 other
Indian soldiers and 11 military observers at nearby Kailahun.
</P>
<P>
The RUF rebels began seizing U.N. soldiers in early May,
leaving the Lome peace accord they signed with the government in
July 1999 in tatters.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council is considering a draft resolution, which
calls for the immediate and unconditional release of all remaining
U.N. soldiers either taken hostage or surrounded by the RUF rebels.
</P>
<P>
The RUF rebels are still calling for the release of their
leader, Foday Sankoh, who is being held at a secret location by
the government since he was arrested in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
