<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Senate Passes Clarity Act on Quebec </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian Senate passed the
Liberal government's bill on the issue of Quebec Thursday night to
make it law against secession of the French-speaking province from
Canada.
</P>
<P>
The bill, better known as Clarity Act since it was passed by
the House of Commons in the middle of March, won the approval of
the Senate with 52 votes for, 34 against and nine abstaining.
</P>
<P>
The Liberal government's Bill C-20, first tabled last December,
enshrines into law a 1998 Supreme Court decision that found Quebec
must win a clear majority from a clearly-worded question before it
can separate from Canada.
</P>
<P>
"We need a clear question and a clear majority," as was once
declared by Prime Minister Jean Chretien, who strongly indicated
that fifty plus one was far short of what he called the majority.
</P>
<P>
Federal Intergovernmental Affairs Minister Stephane Dion
indicated Thursday that another referendum is much less likely now
that the Clarity Act is law.
</P>
<P>
The law leaves it to the House of Commons to judge whether a
future referendum question is clear, and whether the voting
majority is large enough to begin separation negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Quebec Premier Lucien Bouchard has repeatedly declared his will
to launch a third independence referendum in Quebec within his
term of office. The first two referendums were respectively held
in 1980 and 1995 and ended in short of a fifty-plus-one majority,
which separatists believe to be a result of validity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
