<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Memorial Marking "Hanaoka Incident" Held in Northeastern Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A ceremony marking the 55th
anniversary of the "Hanaoka Incident" in which some 130 forced
Chinese laborers in Japan were slaughtered during an uprising at
the end of World War II was held Friday in Akita Prefecture in
northeastern Japan.
</P>
<P>
Hajime Kobatake, mayor of the Odate city, extended condolences
to the victims of the incident in an address at the ceremony which
was sponsored by the Odate municipal government.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-five years have passed since the incident occurred, but
the wounded hearts of the victims' relatives have not yet healed,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Kobatake said that Japan and China should make unremitting
efforts to promote peace and friendship between the two countries
so as to realize a permanent world peace.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 people, including officials from the Chinese Embassy
in Japan, Odate municipal government officials and representatives
of local civic groups, attended the ceremony, which was held
before a monument within a park in Hanaoka town.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the ceremony offered a minute of silent prayer
after Kobatake presented a list of victims to the monument.
</P>
<P>
Geng Shuoyu, son of then uprising leader Geng Chun, delivered a
memorial address at the ceremony on behalf of his father.
</P>
<P>
Angered at the hard labor, more than 700 Chinese laborers
forcibly brought to Hanaoka town by Japanese aggressor troops in
China launched an uprising on June 30, 1945. The uprising was
suppressed by Japanese military police and more than 130 laborers
were killed in the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
