<HEADLINE> Japan's Former Construction Minister Arrested in Bribe Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Former Construction Minister
Eiichi Nakao was arrested Friday by Tokyo prosecutors for
allegedly accepting 30 million yen (285,700 dollars) in bribes
from a construction company, the Kyodo News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
Nakao, 70, a veteran politician of the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) who lost his House of Representatives seat
in Sunday's general election, is suspected of receiving the money
from Tokyo-based Wakachiku Construction Co. in connection with the
selection of construction companies to join the Construction
Ministry's designated bidding firms.
</P>
<P>
Wakachiku Construction is listed on the First Section of the
Tokyo Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo District Public Prosecutors Office on Friday also
raided Nakao's residences in Tokyo and Kofu, Yamanashi Prefecture,
and related offices.
</P>
<P>
In October 1996, the then chairman of Wakachiku Construction
approached Nakao, construction minister at the time, requesting
the company be chosen as one of the ministry's designated bidding
firms, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
In return for agreeing, Nakao allegedly received the money from
the chairman.
</P>
<P>
Nakao, a Kofu native who was first elected to the House of
Representatives in 1967 and won nine lower house elections since,
has also served as minister of international trade and industry
and Economic Planning Agency chief.
</P>
<P>
Nakao was seeking his 11th win in the general election Sunday
but lost the race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
