<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Establish Asia's Biggest Information System for Civil Aviation, Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- China is to pour 1.26 billion yuan
into the making of Asia's most comprehensive information system
for civil aviation and tourism in the next three years, according
to a senior official with the Civil Aviation Administration of
China (CAAC).
</P>
<P>
"To manage the enormous network, we have established the China
Aviation Information Co. Ltd. with 20 other domestic airlines, and
expect to list it on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange." said Yang Jun,
general manager of the Civil Aviation Computer Information Center
under CAAC, in an interview with Xinhua here today.
</P>
<P>
The global distribution system (GDS) is a large computer
information service system that can be applied to civil aviation
and tourism as the connection between the two industries becomes
closer.
</P>
<P>
According to Yang, the GDS, based on the ticket-selling system,
is able to provide real-time and accurate information for
travelers, help CAAC keep up-to-date with sales of domestic
airlines, as well as promote the informationalization on the
country's tourist market.
</P>
<P>
The world's eight top GDSs are distributed throughout Germany,
the United States, Japan, Republic of Korea and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The appearance of GDS here can help China to someday be
included on the list of countries with advanced civil aviation
industries.
</P>
<P>
Since China has been one of the most important markets of civil
aviation and tourism, the competition among the GDS-operating
countries will become more intense after China's entry to the
World Trade Organization, said Yang.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that China's civil aviation passenger
volume reached 60 million in 1999, ranking seventh in the world.
</P>
<P>
Yang also pointed out that a domestically-developed GDS is
necessary if Chinese airlines want to be globally competitive,
because use of foreign GDS services will increase operational
costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
