<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OIC Wants Equal Share of Benefits of Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Foreign Ministers of the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) Friday stressed the need
to take effective measures to alleviate the negative impact of the
international economic order on the economies of member states in
order to guarantee their sharing on an equal footing the benefits
of globalization.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the liberalization of trade has not been beneficial
to the developing countries, they highlighted, in a Communique
issued at the end of their four-day meeting here, the need for
confidence-building in the multilateral trade exchange system by
encouraging the participation of all developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The minister at their 27th meeting also emphasized the
principle of opening up membership of WTO to all, and called for
speeding up the procedure for joining that organization without
any condition in the areas of trade, investment, and stock markets
and technology, so as to achieve the ultimate objective of
establishing a common Islamic market or any other form of economic
complimentarity.
</P>
<P>
They stressed the need to urgently implement the Strategy and
the Plan Action to strengthen economic and commercial cooperation
among member states within the framework of the Standing Committee
for Economic and Commercial Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The ministers stressed the need to make substantial reductions
in the debts of the Least Developed Countries and especially to
observe flexibility in applying the eligibility criteria for
benefiting from the initiative to assist poor debt-burdened
countries.
</P>
<P>
They made an appeal to the developed countries to implement the
'90s Action Plan for the Least Developed and Land-Locked Countries
as well as the other resolutions adopted by the U.N.
</P>
<P>
They welcomed the U.N. decision to convene the third U.N.
Conference on Least-Developed Countries in the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
They renewed the call to the developed countries to offer
substantial reduction of the debts of African countries, including
OIC Member States, and the alleviation of the debt service charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Welcomes OIC Mission to Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government welcomed
Friday the reported plan of the Organization of Islamic Conference
(OIC to send a probe team to the Philippines to determine the true
situation in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said the government does not
consider the mission as an interference, but an opportunity for
the Philippines to show that it is doing its best to bring
development to the south and fully implement a peace agreement it
forged with the Moro National Liberation Front four years ago.
</P>
<P>
"We have no problem with that. It is better that the OIC sees
things for itself," Zamora said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said the government expects the mission to arrive in
three to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Orlando Mercado of the Department of National Defense
also agreed with Zamora's view that the visit of the OIC team
would give the Philippines the chance to prove that it is giving
priority to Mindanao's development.
</P>
<P>
"It would be better if they saw for themselves the situation in
Mindanao," Mercado said in a separate radio interview.
</P>
<P>
Mercado noted that the OIC earlier urged Muslim minorities to
respect the sovereignty and laws of their home countries.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the OIC's call for a stop to military
offensives against the secessionist Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) in Mindanao was uncalled for, as the military was only
responding to the MILF's abuses and violations of the law.
</P>
<P>
The military earlier admitted to launching an all-out war
against the MILF, resulting in the capture of most of the rebel
group's camps and the displacement of thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
The conflict is one of the major issues before the OIC, which
is holding a meeting in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Mercado also said the government continues to weigh its options
in dealing with the MILF, now that the June 30 deadline for a
peace agreement will lapse soon.
</P>
<P>
"Our next move will depend on the MILF's response to the
deadline. We have to protect our territorial integrity," Mercado
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
