<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Expects More Jobs Created in Second Half of 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Friday that it expects more jobs to be created in the 3rd and 4th
quarters of 2000 despite the country's unemployment rate rising to
a nine-year high level of 13.9 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
Labor Secretary Bienvenido Laguesma said April's unemployment
rate was resulted from the decrease in seasonal or part-time
agricultural jobs.
</P>
<P>
"The jobs decrease last April was due mainly to factors
affecting the agricultural, fishery and forestry sector which is
adjusting itself while bracing for stronger food security programs
of the government," Laguesma said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The labor chief stressed that despite the rise in unemployment,
" the economy is not in bad shape," citing that the unexpected"
increase was due "almost entirely to the steep fall of 1.502
million workers in agricultural employment.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that agricultural employment would perk up in
the next quarter based on the Department of Agriculture's forecast
of a 3.5 percent increase in farm output.
</P>
<P>
The survey of the National Statistics Office (NSO) also showed
that the employment slump pushed up the services sector by 404,000
jobs as "surplus agricultural labor sought employment elsewhere."
</P>
<P>
The NSO report pointed to the conflict in the Autonomous Region
in Muslim Mindanao as one of the factors that decreased the labor
force by 570,000 to 32.874 million in April 2000 from 33.444
million in the same month of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Around 86.1 percent of the country's labor force were employed
in April 2000 -- 10.59 million in agriculture, fishery and
forestry; 4.57 million in industry; and 13.17 million in services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
