<HEADLINE> Orlando Magic Ready to Sign NBA Free-agent Stars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Orlando Magic has set
sights on superstars Tim Duncan and Grant Hill when the free-agent
sweepstakes begins on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Magic, a surprise 41-41 last season under first-year coach
Doc Rivers, cleared about 18 million US dollars of salary-cap room
as it became the big wheelers and dealers in the NBA draft on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We're loaded. We have the money we needed now, and we don't
have to worry about giving away our whole team or doing any sign-
and-trade deals," said Rivers, coach of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Magic had three first-round picks in the draft but kept
only Mike Miller, dealing the other two and veterans Corey
Maggette and Derek Strong to get the extra cap room.
</P>
<P>
Current contracts of all free agents expire on Saturday, but no
one can be signed until August 1 when the salary cap for next
season is announced.
</P>
<P>
The thought of Duncan and Hill going to the same team could
shift the balance of power in the NBA from Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe
Byrant and the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
And Magic has made the necessary moves by being able to offer
both Duncan and Hill a maximum six-year contract starting at 9
million US dollars a year with 10 percent annual raises.
</P>
<P>
However, due to the salary cap restrictions, it will take some
major maneuvering for both superstars to end up on the same team.
</P>
</TEXT>
