<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Funeral For U.N. FAO Staffer Held in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A funeral was held Friday for Yusuf
Abdilleh, a Somali national who was killed Wednesday in the Iraqi
capital by a gunman who claimed to protest the U.N. sanctions on
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Abdilleh, an administrative officer of the United Nations Food
and Agriculture Organization (FAO), was buried at the Karh cemetery
in a Baghdad suburb.
</P>
<P>
Abdilleh was one of the two FAO staffers killed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The other one, an Iraqi, was identified as Marewan Mohammed
Hassan. It is not immediately known whether a funeral will also be
held for him.
</P>
<P>
At the memorial ceremony held before the funeral, Hasam Abdul
Razag, an Iraqi foreign ministry adviser, expressed "regret" over
the tragic accident.
</P>
<P>
Amir Khalil, FAO representative in Iraq, extended his thanks for
those attending the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Vice Agricultural Minister Abdul Najim Ali,
representatives of other U.N. organizations in Iraq and diplomatic
corps were present at the ceremony which was held near the FAO
office building in central Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy happened on Wednesday morning when the gunman burst
into the FAO building, killing two FAO staffers and injuring
several others.
</P>
<P>
After a two-hour confrontation with the Iraqi security forces,
the gunman, identified as 38-year-old Fuad Haidar, surrendered to
the authorities.
</P>
<P>
According to him, he did this to protest the decade-old U.N.
sanctions imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has said the sanctions has claimed lives of over 1.2
million people, most of them children and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
Haidar told reporters that he has long had the idea of attacking
a U.N.-affiliated organization in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
He said he originally plotted to abduct U.N. arms inspectors
including the former head of the U.N. Special Commission Richard
Butler, but did not succeed.
</P>
<P>
This time he chose to attack the U.N. FAO because "there are
many foreigners in this organization."
</P>
<P>
It is still unclear that what kind of penalty he will receive,
but he is likely to face death penalty according to the Islamic
law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
