<HEADLINE> Philippines, Spain Sign Friendship Treaty  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
and visiting Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar signed Friday
a treaty that sets the framework for a new partnership between the
two countries in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the Philippines-Spain General Friendship and
Cooperation Treaty was held at the Presidential Palace. The
Spanish prime minister arrived for a three-day visit to the
Philippines on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
The newly signed accord, which replaces the Treaty of
Friendship signed in 1947 by the Philippines and Spain, provides
the parameters for a new partnership in the areas of political,
economic, scientific, technical cultural and educational
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister Aznar and I are committed to translating the
provisions of this treaty into concrete and sustained action
measures," President Estrada said after signing the pact.
</P>
<P>
Estrada also stressed the need for a new and more enduring
Philippine-Spanish partnership, "as both our countries face the
challenges of the new millennium."
</P>
<P>
After signing the treaty, the two leaders witnessed the signing
of a memorandum of understanding on financial cooperation by
officials of the National Economic and Development Authority of
the Philippines and the Ministry of Economy of Spain. 
</P>
