<HEADLINE> Switzerland to Return First Sum of Former Nigerian Leaders' loot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is to recover the first sum
of money looted by former military rulers by next month, President
Olusegun Obasanjo said in Geneva, Switzerland, the Nigerian press
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The press quoted the president as saying on Thursday that the
identified looted funds currently in banks of Switzerland and some
other European countries have amounted to about 3 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo was in Switzerland to attend a special summit of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president expressed disappointment with some
European countries on the issue, urging them to emulate
Switzerland which, according to him, actually used to be "a haven
for loot".
</P>
<P>
He said: "At this juncture, I want to express our appreciation
to the Swiss authorities for cooperating with us to trace and
freeze what we have identified as Nigeria's funds stashed away
illegally and fraudulently to this country (Switzerland)".
</P>
<P>
He added: "Measures to repatriate such funds on both sides are
being taken. And we would have thought that similar countries
harboring Nigeria's stolen funds would consider the Swiss example
for emulation". 
</P>
