<HEADLINE> Chinese Cultural News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are the highlights
of cultural news stories Xinhua released from June 23 to June 29:
</P>
<P>
-- Recovered National Treasure Put on Show in Beijing
</P>
<P>
An antique show opened in the Capital Museum in Beijing on June
24 featuring a national treasure that was looted by the British
and French troops in 1860 and recovered at an auction fair
overseas.
</P>
<P>
The national treasure, a Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) hexagonal
porcelain vase, was purchased by the Beijing Cultural Relics
Company for 20.95 million Hong Kong dollars at an auction fair in
Hong Kong in early May. There are also another 30 precious Chinese
antiques the company recovered from overseas in recent years.
</P>
<P>
-- China Becomes International Dunhuang Studies Center
</P>
<P>
An international symposium on Dunhuang studies will be held
next month in Dunhuang of northwest China's Gansu Province to mark
the centennial anniversary of the discovery of the Sutras Cave and
the beginning of Dunhuang Studies.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman with the Institute of Dunhuang Studies announced on
June 26 that a series of activities would be held from July 29
through August 3 in both Beijing and Gansu.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese, Spanish PMs Watch Dance Performance
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji and visiting Spanish Prime Minister
Jose Maria Aznar watched a performance by artists of the Spanish
Joaquin Cortes dance troupe at the Century Theater on June 26
evening.
</P>
<P>
The performance, jointly sponsored by the Chinese Ministry of
Culture, the Spanish Embassy in Beijing, and the General Society
for Authors and Editors of Spain, was to mark Prime Minister Aznar
' s visit to China.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese-American Oil Paintings Exhibition Held in Beijing
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony of an exhibition of oil paintings by Susan
Tsu, a Chinese-American painter, was held on June 27 in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Susan Tsu was born in Chongqing city in southwest China in 1939.
Her works have been shown in the United States and Mexico many
times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cultural News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Deng's Biography Published
</P>
<P>
"My Father Deng Xiaoping in the Cultural Revolution," a
biography written by Deng's daughter Maomao has come off the press.
</P>
<P>
The book, with 120 family photographs, gives a biographical
account of Deng Xiaoping during the decade-long Cultural
Revolution (1966-1976).
</P>
<P>
-- Seminar on Sino-European Cultural Exchanges Opens
</P>
<P>
An academic seminar on Sino-European cultural exchanges jointly
sponsored by the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences and Nanjing
University opened on June 28 in Nanjing, capital of east China's
Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Papers submitted to the seminar include basic features of
Chinese and European cultures, Chinese cultural environment for
European investors and culture's role in Sino-European political
and economic relations. Nearly 100 Chinese and European
researchers, officials and enterprise managers attended the
seminar, which is one of 1999-2000 higher education cooperative
projects between China and Europe.
</P>
<P>
-- Dramatized "Souls of Red Crag" Exhibition Welcomed in
Beijing
</P>
<P>
"Souls of Red Crag", a dramatized exhibition in memory of
revolutionary martyrs between 1945 and 1949 received thundering
applauses from a Beijing audience on the June 29 evening.
</P>
<P>
"Souls of Red Crag" was presented by actors from Chongqing
Municipality in west China. It tells how members of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) and their followers fought against the
Kuomintang rulers right before New China was founded in 1949. The
performance was attended by Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing and
Ding Guangen, head of the Publicity Department of the CPC Central
Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
