<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Jobless Rate Dips to 4.6 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Japan's jobless rate dropped 0.2
percentage point in May from April to a seasonally adjusted 4.6
percent for the second consecutive month of decline, the
Management and Coordination Agency said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The number of jobless stood at 3.28 million people,
representing a decrease of 60,000 from a year earlier to mark the
first year-on-year decline in 37 months, the agency said in a
preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, the number of jobless men was down 110,000 from a
year before to 1.96 million, the first decline in 35 months, but
the number of unemployed women grew by 60,000 to 1.33 million.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate for men was 4.6 percent, down 0.4
percentage point, while that for women fell 0.1 percentage point
to 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The improvement in overall employment follows two months of a
record-high jobless rate of 4.9 percent, logged in February and
March.
</P>
<P>
A separate report released Friday by Japan's Labor Ministry
showed that the ratio of job offers to job seekers in May was 0.56,
unchanged from the previous month. The figure shows there were 56
work offers for every 100 job hunters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
