<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 1,000 Fall Ill in Western Japan After Drinking Milk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 people fell sick in
Osaka and five other prefectures in western Japan after drinking
low-fat milk produced by a local Japanese company, the Kyodo News
Service reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The victims, ranging in age from 10 months to 90 years old,
suffered diarrhea, abdominal pains and vomiting after drinking the
milk Tuesday and Wednesday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The milk, packaged in 1-liter and 500-milliliter cartons, was
produced by Snow Brand Milk Products Co. last Friday and Saturday
at the company's factory located in Osaka's Miyakojima Ward.
</P>
<P>
A total of 128,000 cartons were produced during the two-day
period, Snow Brand officials said.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the health authorities said they have yet to
determine the cause of the symptoms.
</P>
<P>
The officials said they had examined a carton of milk provided
by family of the victims, but could not detect any bacteria that
would cause food poisoning.
</P>
<P>
As of 12:30 p.m. local time Friday, a total of 1,199 victims
were reported, with Osaka Prefecture posting the largest number of
victims at 737.
</P>
<P>
Most victims are not in a series condition, health authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Snow Brand announced that it had halted low-fat
milk production at the Miyakojima plant, and said that it would
recall the 298,000 cartons of low-fat milk shipped since Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
