<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Sets Conditions for Diplomatic Ties with Armenia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkey will not establish diplomatic
ties with Armenia until the country ends the Nagorno-Karabakh
dispute with Azerbaijan and its campaign over the so-called "
Armenian genocide," Turkish Daily News Friday quoted a Turkish
diplomat as saying.
</P>
<P>
Four Armenians, invited to attend a meeting on peace in Turkey's
eastern province of Kars by a group of businessmen, were reportedly
deported two days ago from Turkey on the grounds that they were not
officially invited.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has not diplomatically recognized Armenia, a newly
independent neighboring country in Caucasus following the collapse
of the former Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Turkey demands Christian Armenia to solve its territory dispute
with Turkic-speaking Azerbaijan peacefully, and to end its campaign
concerning the so-called genocide against Turks all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Armenia claimed Turkey had committed massive killing of
Armenians in April 1915 while the country was still under Ottoman
rule, pressing for a condemnation bill against Ankara concerning
this historical atrocity.
</P>
<P>
Turkey denied the so-called "Armenian genocide."
</P>
<P>
Also, Ankara insisted the disputed Nagorno-Karabakh, now
controlled by Armenia, belongs to Muslim Azerbaijan, Turkey's close
ally in Caucasus, urging Armenia to end the 12-year conflict which
has claimed 35,000 lives on both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
