<HEADLINE> Opposition Leader Elected Solomons PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The opposition leader of the
Solomon Islands, Mannesseh Sogavare, Friday was elected the
country's prime minister, the Australian Broadcasting Corporation
(ABC) reported.
</P>
<P>
After a parliamentary meeting that lasted for two hours,
Solomons Governor-General John Ini Lapli emerged with the new
prime minister to announce that Sogavare had won the vote 23 to 21,
the ABC said.
</P>
<P>
Sogavare said after his election that he would commit his
government to national unity and reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
He also pledged himself to finding peace in the country, the
ABC said.
</P>
<P>
Six members of the Solomon Islands parliament were not present,
including three who refused to fly to the capital Honiara on
Friday, following an incident in which the pilot was threatened by
armed men before he left Honiara to pick them up.
</P>
<P>
Sogavare now replaces former Prime Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'
alu who was forced to resign by an armed militia group, which is
in control of Honiara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
