<HEADLINE> Kenya to Fire Over 42,000 Civil Servants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government will lay off
the first group of 25,783 civil servants beginning on July 1,
Civil Service Reform Secretariat Program Director George Nzioka
has said.
</P>
<P>
The retrenchment, contained in this year's budget released on
June 15, is divided into three phases which will end on January 1,
2002. It will involve a total of 42,329 civil servants, the East
African Standard newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the program, the second phase involving the
retrenchment of 6,565 servants will be carried out between
January and July 2001, and the last phase affecting 9,981 will be
effected between July 2001 and January 2002.
</P>
<P>
Civil servants to be axed include 7,815 from the Environment
and Natural Resources Ministry, 9,500 from the Office of the
President and 3, 577 from the Agriculture and Rural Development
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Nzioka said the exercise is supposed to improve service
delivered to the public and will be carried out on the basis of
past performance records. 
</P>
</TEXT>
