<HEADLINE> DPRK Red Cross Urges S. Korea to Reach Agreement on Humanitarian Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Red Cross Association of the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) on Friday urged its
counterpart of South Korea to reach an agreement at an earlier
date between the two sides on some humanitarian issues, the Korean
Central News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In order to fully implement the historic North-South Joint
Declaration, the issues such as exchange of visiting groups of
separated families and relatives and repatriation of unconverted
long-term prisoners should be discussed without any delay, said a
DPRK Red Cross Association official who is holding talks with a
South Korean delegation at Mount Kumgang Hotel.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the DPRK side put forward a new proposal so
that the two sides could reach an agreement, the official stressed.
</P>
<P>
The new proposal includes:
</P>
<P>
1. The north and south will exchange 100-member visiting groups
of separated families and relatives, first of all, on the occasion
of the coming August 15.
</P>
<P>
2. The repatriation of all the unconverted long-term prisoners
who want to return to the northern half of Korea will be made in
early September.
</P>
<P>
3. The Red Cross talks will continue to discuss and settle the
issue of arranging the rendezvous for separated families and
relatives along with this.
</P>
<P>
The two sides held their first meeting at Mount Kumgang Hotel
Tuesday. But they did not reach an agreement due to differences
between the two sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
