<HEADLINE> Seoul, Pyongyang Reach Agreement on Reunion of Separated Families </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Red Cross delegations from Seoul
and Pyongyang on Friday agreed to arrange a reunion for separated
family members from each side in August and to repatriate DPRK
prisoners back to Pyongyang in September.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed at Mount Kumgang Hotel in the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) Friday afternoon
after a four-day negotiation, according to the South Korean Red
Cross.
</P>
<P>
It is a further tangible result of the inter-Korean summit in
Pyongyang on June 13-15, at which South Korean President Kim Dae-
jung and DPRK top leader Kim Jong Il agreed to address
humanitarian issues.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, a total of 151 people from each side will
consist of one team leader, 100 family members, 30 accompanying
delegates and 20 reporters. They will visit Seoul and Pyongyang
August 15-18 respectively.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is expected to send all 58 DPRK prisoners back to
Pyongyang by early September.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to designate a formal venue for the
family reunions soon after the DPRK prisoners are repatriated to
Pyongyang in early September.
</P>
<P>
The two governments will hand over a list of 200 people each
before the reunions to verify that their family members are still
alive after the Korean peninsula was divided for more than five
decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
