<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Annuls Prisoner Categorization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of Nepal has
annulled the process of categorizing prisoners and treating them
according to their social status, The Kathmandu Post said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The court made the decision on Thursday, citing that
categorization clashed with the constitutional provision of equal
rights, the English daily said.
</P>
<P>
Prisoners in Nepal were so far categorized into "A-class" and"B-
class" depending upon their educational qualification as well as
their living standard. The daily allowance along with other
facilities such as food and clothes varies with the class they
were categorized into.
</P>
<P>
Two advocates had filed a petition in 1996 to cancel the
categorization process, claiming that it favored inequality.
</P>
<P>
The Law and Justice Committee of Nepal proposed to annul the
process of prisoner categorization during the last session of the
parliament in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
