<HEADLINE> Zambia Spends 130 Million U.S.Dollars on Debt Servicing Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is currently spending over
130 million U.S. dollars annually on debt repayment to service its
six billion dollars foreign debt, Vice President Christon Tembo
has said.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's Daily Mail Friday quoted Tembo as saying the debt
repayment is a challenge the country has to tackle in order to
eradicate poverty.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a conference on Poverty Reduction Strategy Paper
(PRSP) in Lusaka on Thursday, Tembo said the country's ability to
service the debt is dependent on what the country exports, while
debt servicing consumes sixteen percent of export earnings.
</P>
<P>
He added that due to the debt servicing burden, the government
considers the Heavily Indebted Poor Country (HIPC) program as a
welcome arrangement for debt relief. 
