<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, June 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton Thursday released 20
million U.S. dollars in energy aid to provide oil to the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Under a 1994 agreement, the United States, Japan and South
Korea founded a group to supply the DPRK with two light-water
nuclear reactors and heavy fuel oil in exchange for the DPRK's
promise to freeze its nuclear development program. Clinton said in
a certification Thursday that the DPRK appeared to be living up to
its commitment to freeze its nuclear weapons program. Under U.S.
law, Clinton must certify that the DPRK has terminated its nuclear
weapons program before he moves to release such funds. (US-DPRK-
Aid)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
VIENNA -- Austrian President Thomas Klestil was disappointed at
the decision of the European Union (EU) Thursday to maintain
political sanction against his country, a presidential statement
said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Klestil considered the EU decision a possible start to lift the
political embargo, but he was disappointed that the EU did not
indicate an end to the sanction nor propose a timetable when it
planned to evaluate the situation in Austria, said the statement.
The EU decision mandates Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio
Guterres to ask the European Court of Human Rights to appoint a
three-member panel to conduct a thorough review of the political
situation in Austria and draw up a report. Portugal is holding the
rotating EU presidency. (Austria-EU-Disappointment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said Thursday he was
still uncertain whether it is the right time for him to have a
summit with Israeli and Palestinian leaders to hammer out a final
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
"I am going to do whatever I can in the time I have left to
help them (Israelis and Palestinians) make peace but whatever I do
or don't do will be based on my calculation that it will maximize
the possibility of... ultimate success," Clinton said. Asked if he
expected to make a decision on whether to invite Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian President Yasser Arafat to
come to the United States for summit in the next day or two,
Clinton replied: "No." (US-Clinton-Middle East)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- Former German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who was under
investigation by a parliamentary panel on campaign finance scandal,
rejected all charges against him Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before the panel, Kohl refused to disclose the name of
those who provided 2 million marks to his Christian Democrats
party during 1993 to 1998. Kohl said he knew little about his
party's finance system and had no knowledge about the party's
alleged secret accounts in Swiss banks. Last December, Kohl
admitted that he received up to 2 million marks as undeclared
party donations and ran secret bank accounts in 1990s, offending
Germany's Party Funding Law. (Kohl-Testimony) 
</P>
</TEXT>
