<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Medicine Gains Popularity in World Market (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Tibet, known as the "roof of the
world," will attract global attention next month with the 2000
International Symposium on Tibetan Medicine to be held in the
capital city of Lhasa.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 experts on Tibetan medicine will be in the city
July 15-17 to discuss the development of Tibetan medicine and
search for ways to preserve this unique, ancient system of medical
treatment in the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
The symposium will be the first of its kind ever held in the
homeland of Tibetan medicine, demonstrating that Tibetan medicine
has won the recognition of people around the globe.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan medicine, with a history of more than 2,500 years, has
been used by Tibetan people for years to ward off diseases of
various kinds. Tibetan medicine is used to treat arthritis,
gastritis, gastric ulcers and altitude sickness.
</P>
<P>
The Qinghai-Tibet plateau has 2,100 kinds of herbs, 150 species
of animal and 40 types of minerals which can be used as
ingredients in Tibetan medicine. Over 50 pharmaceutical factories
specializing in Tibetan medicine have been built in Tibet, Qinghai,
Sichuan, Gansu and Yunnan provinces with a combined annual output
value of 400 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
A British tourist, surnamed Jennings, who has been traveling in
Tibet, said that before she left the plateau, she had visited a
Tibetan doctor, took a medicated bath and bought a large quantity
of Tibetan medicine to take home.
</P>
<P>
"I want my family members and friends to experience the magical
medicine with me," she said.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners don't need to travel all the way to Tibet for
medical treatment or to buy medicine, because China has opened
Tibetan medicine centers in north America, Europe and southeast
Asia, said Mei Xuedai, an official of the Jinhe Tibetan Medicine
Company in Qinghai Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Cultural Charm Revives Hunting Skill (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The skill has been a pride of the Jins for several generations.
Only one man of a generation could be taught with the secret
hunting skill of the family which has lived off hunting for
hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
Once regarded as a fearless and skilled hunter by his fellow
villagers, 69-year-old Jin gave up hunting some 20 years ago
because he saw the population of wild animals in the area
decreasing. Then a stroke in 1997 left him partially paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
"I have no family members who are hunters now," Jin said. "It
is a pity if our ancestral skill got lost in my generation."
</P>
<P>
Gazing at his shotgun hanging on the wall, Jin Xuetian is lost
in a cloud of memories as he lies motionless on his adobe bed.
</P>
<P>
Jin, now bedridden, is the 11th generation of the hunters'
family who has lived at Mount Changbai since the late 14th Century,
and gained acclaim for their abilities to understand the languages
of birds and animals.
</P>
<P>
Out in the wild, the Jins "talked" to birds and beasts by
imitating their sounds and voices. Jins always caught more animals
than other hunters, and often shared their bounty with neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Jin's father selected the eager teenager from five sons and
daughters to learn the family's secret hunting skill. By blowing
on a leaf between his lips, Jin could produce up to 20 different
animal voices.
</P>
<P>
He seldom returned from a hunt empty-handed, often capturing
deer, boars, and bears. His legendary exploits include killing
seven wild boars in a single day, and several narrow escapes from
ferocious tigers.
</P>
<P>
Shisidaogou Township, Jin's home in northeast China's Jilin
Province, is close to Mount Changbai, which stretches southeast
into the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
In the early 1950s, tens of thousands of hunters still
inhabited the area where their ancestors had lived off hunting for
thousands of years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Cultural Charm Revives Hunting Skill (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the 1970s the provincial government banned hunting in some
parts of Mount Changbai, a national nature reserve known for the
most diversified species in the northeast.
</P>
<P>
Jin and thousands of other hunters had to move from the forests.
He became a farmer, learning to work the land with strong hands
unfamiliar with anything but the barrel of a gun.
</P>
<P>
He and his three children planted crops, fruit trees, and
medicinal herbs to make a living.
</P>
<P>
But Jin misses the forest. Back when he was able, he trekked
through the woods imitating voices of birds and animals. However
he never shot at them again but for soothing his nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
What makes him sad now is not that he couldn't hunt but he
could not speak clearly due to stroke, meaning he could not pass
on the secret skill.
</P>
<P>
Jin used to have three volumes of journals, passed down from
his ancestors, which detailed each hunting expedition of the
family, as well as the "meanings" of various bird chirps and
animal howls, and hunters' wiles. The journals were titled "Happy"
because the hunters were always happy when they returned home with
full hands.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately the three volumes were burned during the Cultural
Revolution (1966-76).
</P>
<P>
Jin's story has captured the attention of a number of noted
scholars, including Cao Baoming, a world-renowned Chinese folklore
expert. At the request of the expert, Jin once performed his
family skill by making a kind of noise. And just in a while a
group of squirrels rushed to the scene.
</P>
<P>
Cao has interviewed Jin several times, trying to recapture the
content of "Happy" by encouraging Jin to recall the details from
his memory.
</P>
<P>
"The books on hunting are an essential record of human beings'
fight for survival," Cao said. "They provide real scientific
meaning and rich cultural resources. We should not only protect
the endangered wildlife but also developing the endangered hunting
culture."
</P>
<P>
The folklorist and the hunter share the same hope that Jin
would recover one day so that he could teach people the skill only
he himself knows, with purposes other than hunting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exhibition To Show China's Century-Old Oil Painting History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition on oil paintings
created in the past century by major Chinese artists is soon to be
held in Beijing, which will show the century-old history of China'
s oil painting development.
</P>
<P>
This is the largest oil painting showcase event ever held in
China.
</P>
<P>
On display are more than 400 works by over 270 artists,
including such renowned ones as Xu Beihong, Liu Haisu and Wu
Zuoren, as well as Chinese pioneers in oil painting art like Li
Tiefu, Li Shutong and Lin Fengmian.
</P>
<P>
Among the exhibits, about 40 to 50 pieces were provided by
overseas art organizations and individual collectors.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition highlights those works with the spirit of times,
Chinese characteristics or individual characteristics, which
combined Europe's oil painting art with China's traditional
culture.
</P>
<P>
Oil painting, symbol of Western drawing, was introduced to
China a century ago. Current Chinese oil painting is a produce of
the mix of Chinese and Western cultures, according to Zhang Zuying,
secretary-general of the organizing committee of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Chinese oil painting has arouse worldwide attention as it not
only bears heritage of generations but also has developed into a
unique art form with characteristics of Chinese nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
