<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tehran Starts Runoff Election for Majlis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Iran's capital Tehran started a
runoff election for the sixth Majlis (parliament) Friday morning,
with four candidates running for two seats in the 290-member
legislative body.
</P>
<P>
The vote casting in some 2,124 ballot boxes in the constituency
started at 0900 local time (0430 GMT) and will last at least 10
hours. The result is to be announced within a maximum of 24 hours
after the end of the polling, the Election Headquarters at the
Interior Ministry has announced.
</P>
<P>
Among the four candidates is prominent reformist figure Ali
Akbar Mohtashamipur, publisher of the popular Persian-language
daily "Bayan" (Expression) which was closed by the conservative
judiciary just days ahead of the runoff election.
</P>
<P>
Mohtashamipur, a presidential advisor and former interior
minister, has also been summoned by the special clerical court, but
he has refused to appear before the court, saying the guideline
of "Bayan" is to help national reforms advocated by President
Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Iran's first-round parliamentary election was held on February
18, which resulted in a landslide victory of reformers over their
conservative rivals. A runoff election in constituencies except
Tehran was held on May 5, in which the conservatives also suffered
a severe defeat.
</P>
<P>
Tehran constituency, the political center of the country, has a
share of 30 seats in the 290-member parliament. In the first-round
election, some 29 of the 30 seats were won by reformers.
</P>
<P>
But the powerful Guardians Council (GC), conservative supervisor
of the election, confirmed only 28 of the winners' list after a
three-month delay, ordering a runoff for the other two winners.
</P>
<P>
Of the 28 winners approved, only two were conservative figures,
including former president and Majlis speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani.
The two were believed to have entered the parliament with help from
the GC.
</P>
<P>
But under pressure from reformers, Rafsanjani, currently heading
the arbitral State Expediency Council, has announced he will not
take his seat in the Majlis, leaving a vacancy to be filled through
a by-election.
</P>
<P>
After severe struggles with the conservative establishment, the
new Majlis, dominated by reformers, managed to start work on May
27.
</P>
<P>
But a number of seats are still vacant due to the delay of
Tehran election results and the GC's annulling of votes. The
conservative body is said to have annulled first-round and runoff
election results in 10 constituencies, involving 12 candidates all
belonging to the reformist camp. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
