<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright returned to
Washington Thursday and briefed U.S. President Bill Clinton on her
discussions with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian
National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Despite assessments from officials on all sides that it is still
premature to hold a three-way summit, Clinton is expected to
announce in the coming days when he will convene one, possibly on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Albright's failure to bring the two sides together prompted
renewed warnings about bloodshed if a peace treaty is not reached
by the September 13 deadline.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- For the second time in a week, official sources in Damascus
were quoted Thursday as saying talks with Israel could resume in
August.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the resumption is conditional on
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's acknowledgement that Syrian
President-designate Bashar al-Assad will stand firm on Syria's
territorial demands, "especially on the return of Syria to the
northern shore of the Kinneret (Sea of Galilee)."
</P>
<P>
However, the sources added "the question of water will remain
open for discussion."
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- The Israeli Council of Chief Rabbinate will meet on Monday
following an appeal from rabbis and political figures to relax an
accepted ruling that prohibits Jews from entering the Temple Mount
in the old city of Jerusalem for reasons related to "impurity" in
the Jewish tradition.
</P>
<P>
Following reports on a forthcoming agreement concerning the
Temple Mount, and amid possibilities that the Palestinian National
Authority will get formal control, the political right has stepped
up pressure on the chief rabbis to change their ruling.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- The Iranian revolutionary court in Shiraz is due to hand down
sentences Saturday to the 13 Iranian Jews charged with spying for
Israel since the beginning of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The last hearing in the two-month trial was held last weekend.
It ended with eight suspects confessing, four denying charges, and
one admitting that he had collected military information for
Israeli's Mossad intelligence service, but denied he ever gave it
to them.
</P>
<P>
Since the arrest of the 13 Jews, along with eight Muslims, on
the espionage charges, Israel and other western countries have been
pressuring Iran to free the defendants. Meanwhile, Iranian
officials have been making various, sometimes contradictory,
statements about the Jews on trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
