<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Business Confidence Level Lowest Since 1987 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Business confidence in New
Zealand crashed to crisis levels this month, slumping to lows not
seen since the 1987 sharemarket crash, according to the latest
survey of the country's National Bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank's monthly business confidence survey showed that
confidence has now suffered its two biggest falls in consecutive
months in the 12 years of the surveys, falling a further 35 points
to a net 56 percent of respondents expecting general business
conditions to deteriorate during the next year. Pessimists
accounted for 64 percent of replies in June and optimists just for
8 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Two consecutive months of precipitous falls constitute a
crisis in confidence," the Dominion newspaper Friday quoted
National Bank Chief Economist Brendon O'Donovan as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tony Alexander, chief economist of the Bank of New Zealand, was
quoted by the Wellington-based newspaper as saying that business
feels ignored by the government and the confidence figures can be
interpreted as "business sending a message to the government."
</P>
<P>
However, Finance Minister Michael Cullen said Friday in a
government press release that the erosion in business confidence
has been serious, but the mood "is turning around." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
