<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Viagra to Enter China: Pfizer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- More than two years after its
debut, the anti-impotence drug Viagra finally obtains official
approval to enter into China, the world's most populous country.
</P>
<P>
State Drug Administration of China has approved the production
and sale of Viagra in the country, according to the Beijing office
of Pfizer Inc. of the United States, the pharmaceutical giant
which developed the diamond-shaped blue pills. and has net huge
profits from it since April 1998.
</P>
<P>
Pfizer plans to hold a hook-up TV press conference next Monday
in Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou simultaneously, releasing more
details about the launch, said Wang Xunbiao at Pfizer's Beijing
office.
</P>
<P>
Relevant questions such as whether the pill will be available
only with a doctor's prescription and the price of the drug are
expected to be answered at the conference.
</P>
<P>
The Pfizer Pharmaceuticals Inc. in northeast China's Dalian
City, a Chinese unit of the U.S. firm, will produce the drug by
using the imported material, said Lai Wanfeng, a quality-control
manager from the firm.
</P>
<P>
Viagra will be marketed with the registered Chinese name "wan
ai ke", which is literally meaningless, even though the pill has
long been known throughout the country as "weige" - the Chinese
phrase literally meaning "Great Brother".
</P>
<P>
Although there is still no exact statistics of erectile
dysfunction (ED) patients in China, a report provided by Pfizer
states that ED is one of the most serious sexual dysfunction in
males, only after prospermia.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that more than 100 million men are suffering
from ED around the world, the report says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal to Publicize Foreign Aid Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Nepal will soon publicize a
foreign aid policy with the aim to choose assistance projects that
will serve the interests of the country, The Rising Nepal said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Finance Minister Mahesh Acharya told the parliament
Thursday that the policy formation concerning foreign assistance
is in its
final stages and will soon be made public, the official English
daily said.
</P>
<P>
"The policy is nearing completion, and as soon as we
incorporate the reactions from the donors and other concerned
agencies with it, it would be made public," said Acharya, who had
promised the policy in the budget for the fiscal year 2000/2001,
to be passed by the parliament next month.
</P>
<P>
Acharya also said the government is going to bring all foreign
assistance under the central audit system so that the assistance
can be more properly used.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary that foreign aid be audited by the Office of
the Auditor General," he said, adding, "Some more laws are
required for this and the government is taking the initiative."
</P>
<P>
Projects directly funded by foreign donors are now audited by
the donors themselves, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We need to talk with donors in this regard and we are doing so,
"said Acharya.
</P>
<P>
Nepal heavily depends on foreign aid for its development
projects.Bilateral and multilateral donors have agreed to extend 1.
25 billion U.S. dollars to Nepal during 2000-2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
