<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Rejects All Charges in Testify </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Former German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl, who was under investigation by a parliamentary panel on
campaign finance scandal, rejected all charges against him
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before the panel, Kohl refused to disclose the name of
those who provided 2 million marks to his Christian Democrats
party during 1993 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
Kohl said he knew little about his party's finance system and
had no knowledge about the party's alleged secret accounts in
Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
Answering the accusation that he had received 30 million marks
of donation in the sale of the Leuna Oil and Chemical Refinery
company to France in 1992, the former Chancellor said it was "
false".
</P>
<P>
Kohl insisted that the tank sale to Saudi Arabia is a political
decision of his government. He also denied he got any rewards from
the German Electronics giant Siemens to allow its illegal
technology exports.
</P>
<P>
According to local media, the testimony was suspended because
of differences of opinions in the panel. It was not known when the
testimony will resume.
</P>
<P>
Last December, Kohl admitted that he received up to 2 million
marks as undeclared party donations and ran secret bank accounts
in 1990s, offending Germany's Party Funding Law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
