<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0030 GMT, June 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Declining telecom stocks sent Europe's markets down
Thursday after a top mobile phone maker aired cautious comments
and investors fretted about signs of a slowdown in the recently
booming sector.
</P>
<P>
London's benchmark FTSE 100 closed down 74.5 points at 6,239,
continuing a run that has seen it lose nearly 300 points courtesy
of falls in six of the last seven sessions. (EU-Stocks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Wall Street stocks fell broadly Thursday as profit
warnings added to the market uncertainty after the Federal Reserve
indicated the need for one more hike in interest rates if risk of
inflation is coming.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 129.75 at 10,398.
04 and the technology heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 63.11 at 3,
877.23. Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 12.43 at 1,442.39.
</P>
<P>
Stocks fell as a number of companies announced separately that
their earnings will miss analysts' expectations in the second
quarter. Among them were Unisys and Goodyear. (New York-Wall
Street)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- High oil prices could give Mexico additional
income close to three billion U.S. dollars this year, said Jose
Antonio Rojas Nieto, a professor at the National Autonomous
University of Mexico (UNAM).
</P>
<P>
This can be attributed to the fact that the income from exports
could surpass that of 1999 when 8.859 billion dollars were
received as the result of a daily average sale of crude abroad of
1.553 million barrels a day (bpd), said Rojas. (Mexico-Oil-Income)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Presidents from Mexico, Guatemala and El
Salvador and the vice president of Honduras signed Thursday in
this capital the Mexico-Northern Triangle Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement that will open a potential market of 124 million
consumers will go into force on January 1, 2001, after approved by
the legislative assembly of each country. (Mexico-Northern-
Triangle)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canada and Russia signed deals worth over 800 million
Canadian dollars (about 541 million U.S. dollars) Thursday in
Moscow, the Canadian government announced.
</P>
<P>
The deals include contracts valued at 385.1 million Canadian
dollars (about 260.4 million U.S. dollars), memorandums of
understanding on mining and geoscience ventures, letters of intent
and a cooperation agreement worth 220 million Canadian dollars. (
Canada-Russia-Deals)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- President Bill Clinton Thursday released 20
million U.S. dollars in energy aid to provide oil to the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Under a 1994 agreement, the United States, Japan and South
Korea founded a group to supply the DPRK with two light-water
nuclear reactors and heavy fuel oil in exchange for the DPRK's
promise to freeze its nuclear development program. (U.S.-DPRK-Aid)
</P>
</TEXT>
