<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Files Charges Against "Love Bug" Creator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has filed
criminal charges against a computer science student suspected of
spreading the "Love Bug" virus that crippled millions of computer
systems worldwide, The Philippine Star said Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the National Bureau of
Investigation(NBI) charged 23-year-old Onel de Guzman Thursday
with credit card fraud in a case hampered by a lack of laws
covering computers.
</P>
<P>
The virus, unleashed on May 4, rapidly replicated itself via e-
mail, overloading corporate e-mail systems in many countries and
causing damage estimated at up to 10 billion U.S. dollars, mainly
in lost man-hours.
</P>
<P>
Until Philippine President Joseph Estrada signed a new law on
June 14 covering electronic commerce and computer hacking, the
country had no legislation specifically for computer crimes.
</P>
<P>
However, the new law can not be applied retroactively to the "
Love Bug" creator and investigators will instead charge de Guzman
with"traditional" crimes such as theft as well as violation of a
law which normally covers credit fraud.
</P>
<P>
The charges carry a maximum penalty of 20 years in prison, NBI
Director Federico Opinion said.
</P>
<P>
De Guzman, a former student of the AMA Computer College, has
acknowledged that he might have released the virus by accident,
but refused to say whether he authored it.
</P>
<P>
He failed to graduate earlier this year after AMA professors
rejected his thesis proposal for a program which steals Internet
passwords, a feature of the Love Bug virus.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Justice will now determine whether the NBI's
evidence against de Guzman is strong enough to warrant a trial.
</P>
<P>
NBI agents seized 17 computer diskettes, telephones and
computer accessories in a raid on May 8 on the suspect's apartment
in Manila, but found no computer or modem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Chinese Dailies Set to Take on New Look </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's three major Chinese
dailies will unveil on July 7 new designs and new editions to
their readers, Singapore Press Holdings officially announced
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lianhe Zaobao, the largest local Chinese daily, will be
elegantly packaged with larger photos and streamlined words to
cater to the needs of the young and busy white-collars.
</P>
<P>
Chew Keng Juea, senior executive vice president of Singapore
Press Holdings, said the redesigned Lianhe Zaobao will be
aesthetically"fresh and modern with a new masthead and visual
pages."
</P>
<P>
"Editorial-wise, stories will be shorter, sharper and reader-
friendly.There will be a section -- ZB Business-- devoted to local,
regional and East Asian business news and analyses," Chew said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Lianhe Wanbao and Shin Min Daily News will
launch their afternoon editions, designed to facilitate people's
reading needs during lunch time
</P>
<P>
"Lianhe Wanbao and Shin Min Daily News will launch their
afternoon editions on July 7, 2000. There will be at least 40
percent difference in content between the afternoon and evening
editions," Chew said.
</P>
<P>
With the launch of the new measures, the three Chinese dailies
will be able to provide readers with round-the-clock news coverage,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The combined reach of the three Chinese dailies is currently 1.
7 million readers with a combined circulation of more than 470,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
