<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The measures aim to improve the deteriorating ecological
conditions in China, especially in the northern part which has
been even more devastated by spring sandstorms sweeping nearly
half of the country, including cities of Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
-- The Xi'an Cellular Engineering Project Development Center
was officially inaugurated over the week in this capital of
northwest China's Shaanxi Province. The state-designated institute
is expected to invigorate China's bio-engineering research.
</P>
<P>
Jointly founded by the No. 4 Medical College of the Chinese
People's Liberation Army and the Shaanxi New and High-Tech
Industries Investment Co., the center will focus on the study of
engineering development of animal cells, cross-breeding tumor
cells, cellular-engineering and cell factor tests.
</P>
<P>
-- A commentary released by Xinhua News Agency said that the
Taiwan compatriots desire to maintain peace and stability across
the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
These are also necessary for social stability and economic
development in Taiwan, the commentary said.
</P>
<P>
The changes in Taiwan's political situation since mid-March
have captured the attention of the compatriots across the Straits,
overseas compatriots and international communities.
</P>
<P>
-- The mainland urged the Taiwan authorities to strictly abide
by the common understanding reached in 1992 between the mainland's
Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) and
Taiwan's Strait Exchange Foundation (SEF) that each of the two
organisations should express verbally that "both sides of the
Taiwan Straits adhere to the One-China principle."
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said at a press
conference that the Taiwan authorities have misinterpreted the One-
China principle.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of such a move by the Taiwan authorities is to try
to inject separatist ideas into the common understanding.
</P>
<P>
-- China's economic performance is showing positive signs that
may nudge the country out of a long period of deflation, according
to the National Bureau of Statistics (NBS).
</P>
<P>
Latest NBS statistics indicate that China's economy developed
in a stable and healthy way in the first five months of the year,
with its gross domestic product (GDP) growth rate expected to
reach 7.5 percent for the whole year. 
</P>
