<HEADLINE> Border Guards And Endangered Animals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese soldiers patrolling the
northwestern borders in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region can
often be seen with wild animals such as red deer, wild donkeys and
gazelles.
</P>
<P>
At least some 15,000 gazelles roam around border sentries,
according to local forestry departments in the autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang is rich in the resources of wild animals including 20
kinds of endangered species. However, the number of wild animals
has been declining due to illegal hunters and traffickers. Some of
the wild animal is on the brink of extinction.
</P>
<P>
Officers and soldiers have taken opportunities to create public
awareness about the protection of wild animals among local people.
</P>
</TEXT>
