<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Rejects OIC Call for Truce in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
rejected a resolution by the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC)urging Manila to stop military operations against
Muslim rebels in Mindanao, Philippine Daily Inquirer said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Press Secretary Ricardo Puno as saying
Thursday that the government would not accede to the request as it
was only carrying out "peace and order operations" and not "real
offensive operation" in some areas in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
"This is an independent country. We have to move in accordance
with our own prerogative and in accordance with the requirements
that confront us whenever it is a question of keeping this country
together," Puno said.
</P>
<P>
The military earlier admitted to launching an all-out war
against the secessionist Moro Islamic Liberation Front in Central
Mindanao,resulting in the capture of most of the rebel group's
camps and the displacement of thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
The conflict is one of the major issues before the OIC, which
brokered a peace agreement between the government and the
mainstream Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The OIC, which is holding a meeting in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia,
has also resolved to send a fact-finding team to Mindanao to
assess rival claims by the government and the MNLF which made
peace four years ago in exchange for autonomy.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government expressed welcome to the fact-finding
mission,pointing out that the OIC resolution was passed with the
Philippine government's concurrence.
</P>
<P>
"We have nothing to hide so it will be better for them to
discover the real situation, to see for themselves," Executive
Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
The team is likely to include representatives from the OIC's
six-nation committee which has been dealing with the insurgency in
Mindanao. The members of the committee are Saudi Arabia, Libya,
Bangladesh, Somalia, Senegal and Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
