<HEADLINE> U.S. to Host Ethiopia-Eritrea Expert-Level Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Expert-level delegations from
Eritrea and Ethiopia will meet in Washington next week to discuss
technical aspects of a recent peace pact following the end of two-
year hostilities between the two East African countries, the U.S.
government confirmed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Philip Reeker said at a regular
briefing that the talks "are scheduled to take place at the State
Department on Monday, July 3."
</P>
<P>
The June 18 accord signed by Eritrea and Ethiopian in Algiers "
left a number of outstanding issues to be resolved before a final
peace agreement can be concluded," Reeker said.
</P>
<P>
The accord brokered by the Organization of African Unity called
for an immediate cease-fire and the deployment of a U.N.
peacekeeping force in a 25-kilometer buffer zone inside Eritrea
until the disputed border is demarcated.
</P>
<P>
Reeker disclosed that President Bill Clinton's former national
security adviser Anthony Lake would play a part in the coming
talks in Washington but gave no further details. 
</P>
