<HEADLINE> Austria Disappointed at EU Decision on Sanction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Austrian President Thomas Klestil
was disappointed at the European Union's decision Thursday to
maintain political sanction against his country, a presidential
statement said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Klestil considered the EU decision a possible start to lift the
political embargo, but he was disappointed that the EU did not
indicate an end to the sanction nor propose a timetable when it
planned to evaluate the situation in Austria, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The EU decision mandates Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio
Guterres to ask the European Court of Human Rights to appoint a
three-member panel to conduct a thorough review of the political
situation in Austria and draw up a report.
</P>
<P>
Portugal, who holds the rotating EU presidency, said in a
statement that the EU member states will re-examine their
relations with Austria on the basis of the panel report.
</P>
<P>
In another communique released the same day, Portugal said that
the political isolation against Austria remains in force.
</P>
<P>
Klestil asked the Austrian government to treat the EU statement
in a constructive manner with the emphasis on making maximum
efforts to safeguard its interests inside the EU.
</P>
<P>
Austrian Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel criticized the EU
decision at a news conference on Thursday, but said that Austrian
government will cooperate with the three-member panel.
</P>
<P>
The EU imposed a political sanction on Austria on February 4
when the far-right Freedom Party was admitted into the Austrian
coalition government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
