<HEADLINE> U.S., Russia to Hold Joint Missile Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Russia
plan to hold a joint theater missile defense exercise based on
computer simulation in Texas late this year, the Pentagon said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Department spokesman Ken Bacon told reporters
that the computer simulation exercise was planned for Fort Bliss,
Texas, in November or December.
</P>
<P>
As to the talks between U.S. and Russian defense officials in
Moscow on Tuesday and Wednesday, Bacon said the two sides did not
resolve a dispute over the U.S. plan to deploy a national missile
defense system.
</P>
<P>
"They have not changed their opposition, and we have not
changed our determination to go forward," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. plan to deploy missile defense system violates the
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty signed by the U.S. and former Soviet
Union in 1972. Russia has so far refused to revise the treaty to
accommodate the U.S. move. 
</P>
</TEXT>
