<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada, Russia Sign Multimillion-dollar Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Canada and Russia signed deals
worth over 800 million Canadian dollars (about 541 million U.S.
dollars) Thursday in Moscow, the Canadian government announced.
</P>
<P>
Canadian International Trade Minister Pierre Pettigrew, who is
heading a trade delegation representing more than 60 Canadian
companies, witnessed the signing of the documents.
</P>
<P>
The deals include contracts valued at 385.1 million Canadian
dollars (about 260.4 million U.S. dollars), memorandums of
understanding on mining and geoscience ventures, letters of intent
and a cooperation agreement worth 220 million Canadian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Prime Minister Viktor Khristenko and Pettigrew
co-chaired a meeting of the Intergovernmental Economic Commission
(IEC) between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The IEC meeting, which concluded Thursday, was devoted to
discussions about ways to enhance cooperation in agriculture, food,
aerospace, construction, mining and high technology.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the IEC session as a success, Pettigrew said in a
statement that "Canada and Russia have much in common and a great
deal we can build on."
</P>
<P>
"While many commercial challenges lie ahead, I believe they can
be overcome through further open dialogue and business forums that
the IEC provides," said the Canadian minister.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian trade delegation left for Moscow Tuesday and was
scheduled to end the mission Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
