<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS -- The Liberian government Thursday announced the release
of 21 Indian U.N. peacekeepers who had been trapped by rebels in
neighboring Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Liberian Information Minister Joe Mulbah said that the group
was now at a Liberian border town and expected in the Liberian
capital Monrovia shortly, according to reports reaching here from
Monrovia. (S. Leone-U.N. peacekeepers-Release)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair Thursday said his
country would take part in the euro zone, but would do so only if
"the economic tests were pleasing." (Germany-Britain)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian police arrested 75 new fascists making
trouble at the Savyolovsky Park in central Moscow Wednesday
evening, reported Russian news agencies Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place at around 21:20 Moscow time (1820 GMT)
Wednesday when a group of about 100 young skinheads giving Nazi-
style salutes gathered near a disco bar in the downtown park after
a rock concert and got into affray and fights, the Moscow Main
Internal Affairs Department told reporters Thursday. (Russia-New
Fascists-Arrest)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council Thursday urged
representatives of all social and political forces in Somalia to
actively take part in the peace process in the Horn of Africa
country.
</P>
<P>
A presidential statement, adopted at the end of the open
Security Council debate on Somalia, said, "The Security Council
underlines the importance of the widest participation of all parts
of Somali society in an effort to rehabilitate Somalia." (UN-
Somali-Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HARARE -- Zimbabwean police spokesman Wayne Bvudzijena said
Thursday that disturbances related to the weekend election results
were reported in Chitungwiza and some suburbs in Harare.
Bvudzijena said in a statement that 12 people were arrested and
one vehicle was burnt in connection with the political
disturbances. (Zimbabwe-Disturbance)
</P>
