<HEADLINE> Sampras Pledges to Battle on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Six-time Wimbledon champion Pete
Sampras has pledged to battle on after a MRI scan on his injured
ankle revealed a strained tendon but no structural damage
following his win over Karol Kucera from Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
Sampras'coach Paul Annacone said the player will continue to
have ice treatment in a bid to fulfil his third-round match with
fellow American Justin Gimelstob.
</P>
<P>
ATP Tour trainer Doug Spreen said: "Pete Sampras underwent an
MRI scan last night and it confirmed acute tendinitis in his left
foot."
</P>
<P>
"Pete has already received treatment and will receive further
treatment later on Thursday. This treatment involves icing,
electrical stimulation and anti-inflammatory medication. He will
rest on Thursday," he said. "We will re-evaluate the situation on
Friday but Pete fully expects to play." 
</P>
</TEXT>
