<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Davenport Back from the Brink </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Lindsay
Davenport of the United States came back from the brink to keep
her grip on the Wimbledon title in a Court One classic on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But third seed and reigning French Open champion Mary Pierce
was not so lucky as she crashed out in straight sets to Spain's
Magui Serna.
</P>
<P>
Davenport, 24, was a double break down in the final set to
Russian Elena Likhovtseva before rallying to complete an
extraordinary 3-6, 6-3, 6-3 win.
</P>
<P>
She was left reeling by Likhovtseva's lightning start, when she
broke Davenport twice to lead 4-0 and had two break points for 5-0.
</P>
<P>
And Davenport, playing only her sixth match since April after
being plagued by a back injury, admitted afterwards: "I got lucky.
"
</P>
<P>
The world number two struggled with her serve as she was broken
five times and had no answer to Likhovtseva's cracking returns and
passing shots.
</P>
<P>
Despite winning the second set after breaking her opponent
twice, Davenport seemed to have thrown it all away when she was
broken in the first and third sets of the final set.
</P>
<P>
Only then did her game finally click into gear and she blazed
through the final six sets to snatch victory.
</P>
<P>
She admitted: "For some reason I'm getting off to really slow
starts. But when I got broken again for 3-0 I started to hit my
shots a little bit better. Those last six games I was hitting the
ball great."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pierce could not find top gear against her 21-year-
old opponent, ranked 49th in the world.
</P>
<P>
Serna held her nerve admirably to triumph in two consecutive
tie-breaks and blow open the bottom half of the draw even more
following the earlier exit of 12th seed Amanda Coetzer.
</P>
<P>
The South African slipped to a 7-6, 6-2 defeat at the hands of
American Lilia Osterloh.
</P>
<P>
But Monica Seles breezed past Belgian Els Callens 6-4, 6-4 to
book her place in the third round.
</P>
<P>
And the sixth seed admitted she was driven by the thought of
adding to her nine major titles and completing a grand slam of the
Grand Slams.
</P>
<P>
"I would love to do well here," said Seles, whose straight sets
thrashing by Steffi Graf in the 1992 final remains the closest she
has got to the title.
</P>
<P>
"It's a challenge every year that I keep facing. I love coming
back here. I love the surroundings. I just wish the surface suited
my game more. Besides that, I love the place," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
