<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Chief in Iraq on Fact-finding Mission EDS-1st lead-writethru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Director General of the United
Nations Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO), Jacques Diouf,
arrived here Friday on a fact-finding visit.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to focus on the tragic accident that two staffers
of the FAO office in Baghdad were killed by a gunman Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The gunman, identified as 38-year-old Fuad Haidar, shot and
killed two FAO staffers -- a Somali and an Iraqi -- and wounded
several others.
</P>
<P>
Haidar, who surrendered to the authorities after a two-hour
confrontation with Iraqi security forces, claimed that his attack
was meant to protest the decade-old U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Diouf said he would meet Iraqi officials to get acquainted with
Wednesday's incident.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after arrival, the FAO chief went to the FAO office
building in central Baghdad and met the staff members there.
</P>
<P>
He also visited the wounded FAO staffers in the hospital and the
Karch cemetery in a Baghdad suburb where the slain Somali FAO
staffer, Yusuf Abdilleh, was buried.
</P>
<P>
Diouf would also meet Iraqi officials from the ministries of
agriculture and irrigation to discuss ways to better implement the
U.N. oil-for-food program, now in its eighth phase.
</P>
<P>
The FAO office in Iraq is mainly in charge of the implementation
of the oil-for-food deal, which allows Iraq to sell limited amount
of oil to buy humanitarian necessities to alleviate the crippling
impacts of the U.N. sanctions in place since Iraq's 1990 invasion
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Fuad Haidar, who is now held in the Jadria Police Bureau in
central Baghdad, told reporters Wednesday evening that he chose to
attack the FAO office because "there are many foreigners in this
organization."
</P>
<P>
He is likely to face the death penalty according to the Islamic
law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs EDS-Retransmitting with correction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- General Manager of the Shell-BP International's
Turkmenistan-Turkey Natural Gas Project Mark Corner said Shell is
determined to bring to fruition the Caspian basin natural gas
pipeline project, reported Turkish Daily News on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement issued prior to a trip to Ashkhabad,
capital of Turkmenistan, Corner said they are working on the
project with their partners General Electric and the Bechtel
Consortium.
</P>
<P>
He said a joint solution encompassing Turkmenistan, Turkey,
Azerbaijan and Georgia is still possible.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish State Minister responsible for economy Recep
Onal invited companies doing business in Balkan countries to take
part in Turkey's economic program, reported Turkish Daily News on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Balkan Chambers, whose term president is Fuat
Miras, chairman of Turkish Union of Chambers and Commodity
Exchanges, kicked off its general convention in Istanbul Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Onal also invited those firms to take advantage of Turkish free
trade zones.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's trade volume with Balkan countries increased from 1.7
billion U.S. dollars in 1998 to 2.3 billion dollars in 1999, making
up 3.5 percent of Turkey's total trade volume.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus' Demokritos company has signed agreements with
Israeli firms Kalanit Carmon and Daemon System on cooperation in
the area of high technology, the local Financial Weekly newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli software firm Kalanit Carmon, with 400 employees, is
considered as a leader in applying and developing software based on
Microsoft technology, while Daemon Systems, which specializes in
Oracle technology, is soon to be listed on the Tel Aviv exchange.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements, the Israeli firms have respectively
acquired a 10 percent stake in Demokritos, the Cyprus high-tech
company.
</P>
<P>
Demokritos will receive highly skilled and technological
support, plus management know-how, from the Israeli firms which
will help establish a software house in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Demokritos will be the sole agent and supplier of Kalanit and
Daemon software products and services for Cyprus and Greece and
vice versa for the Israeli market.
</P>
<P>
Under the guidance of the Israeli companies, Demokritos will be
able to establish a Microsoft Certified Training &AMP; Education Center
and an Oracle Training &AMP; Education University.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's verified natural gas reserves are put at 1.27
trillion cubic meters with the potential stock at 2.1 trillion
cubic
meters, enough to meet local needs for l00 years to come, said
Minister of Petroleum Amin Sameh Fahmi.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by Egyptian daily Al-Ahram on Friday as saying
that Egypt's oil reserves surged to 4.5 billion barrels, and 265
exploration contracts were concluded over the past 25 years
achieving over 400 oil findings.
</P>
<P>
So far, 80 percent of the Egyptian oil sector has been
privatized, said the minister, adding that local consumption of oil
by 2010 would reach 51.5 million tons on an annual basis from 37.5
million tons at present. Natural gas accounted for 12 percent of
local energy consumption in 1982, while the percentage has soared
to 35 percent now, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Egypt refines 55 million tons of crude oil each year, the
minister said, adding three petrochemical factories with a total
capacity of 700,000 tons per year are underway.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon and the Kuwait Fund for Economic Development
(KFED) have inked an agreement, under which a loan of 10.85 million
dinars (35.26 million U.S. dollars) will be used in funding the
project of the eastern entrance of Beirut to the Syrian borders.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also signed a memo of understanding under which
KFED will provide Lebanon with another 20 million dinars (64
million dollars) in funding the South Lebanon Reconstruction
Program.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-term loan will be delivered with a four-year grace
period and 2.5 percent interest rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
