<HEADLINE> UAE Ranked 45th in U.N. Report on Human Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates was
ranked the 45th in the United Nations annual report for the year
2000 on human development in world countries and territories.
</P>
<P>
The report, prepared by the U.N. Development Program (UNDP),
ranked 174 countries and territories based on a human development
index covering real income, life expectancy, health care and
educational standards, reported the official WAM news agency on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The other members of the Gulf Cooperation Council, namely
Kuwait, Bahrain, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and Oman came in positions 36,
41, 42, 75 and 86 respectively in the report.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon was placed at position 82 on the list, Jordan 92,
Tunisia 101, Algeria 107, Syria 111, Egypt 119, Morocco 124, Iraq
126, Sudan 143 and Yemen 148.
</P>
<P>
Canada topped the list, followed by Norway, the United States
and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia, Burkina Faso, Niger and Sierra Leone were put at the
bottom of the list, ranking 171, 172, 173 and 174 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The report, which did not include the Palestinian self-rule
areas and Somalia, said the increasing trend towards globalization
is not a bad development, provided that governments take into
account more than just trade issues when they were considering
international policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
