<HEADLINE> Telecoms Rebound Turns European Stocks Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A rebound of telecoms stocks
boosted Europe's leading markets Friday, after concerns about the
high cost of securing next-generation mobile phone licenses
sparked a sell-off a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
London's benchmark FTSE 100 index ended up 73.7 points,or 1.2
percent, at 6312.7, with telecom company Cable &AMP;Wireless making a
late-day dash, up 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
A range of stocks contributed to the advance but in the lead
was oil major BP Amoco which put on 1.7 percent or 10-1/2 pence to
634p and added 10.5 points to the FTSE.
</P>
<P>
Insurer Royal &AMP; Sun Alliance rose 7.9 percent, topping the list
of FTSE 100 gainers. Publisher Reed International rose 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE Eurotop 300, a broad measure of the region's largest
stocks, rose 1.2 percent, as its technology hardware sub-index,
which includes top mobile-phone makers, rose 5.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax in Frankfurt was up 0.5 percent at 6907.74, led
by retailer Metro, up 4.9 percent with drugs and chemicals maker
Bayer up 3.7 percent and Schering rising 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip CAC 40 in Paris closed up 45.72 points,or 0.7
percent, at 6446.54, led by a 7.2-percent climb for network
equipment maker Alcatel and a 4.5-percent advance for chipmaker
PSTM. 
</P>
</TEXT>
