<HEADLINE> Mexico Rejects Foreign Assessment of Its Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Mexican Foreign Minister
Rosario Green said Friday that her country does not need anybody
from abroad to validate the general elections or judge its
internal processes.
</P>
<P>
Green described as positive the presence of 860 foreign
observers, most of them from the United States, who will watch
Sunday's presidential elections, but remarked that the process is
an internal and sovereign matter of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
"This must not be construed as a theme that excludes or
sidetracks the decision that invited foreign personalities to
witness the cleanliness and transparency of the elections," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican government expects local and foreign observers to
evaluate the effort of Mexicans "so everybody can give testimony
of the firm and resolute advance of democracy in the country,"
said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
The top Mexican diplomat added that her country has taken
decisive steps to guarantee the full transparency of what will be
the most competed elections in the history of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Almost 59 million Mexicans will elect Sunday a successor of the
incumbent President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
Ruling party candidate Francisco Labastida and right-wing
Vicente Fox are the candidates with the highest possibilities of
victory, according to the last polls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
