<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Parliament Authorizes Presence of U.S. Warships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Washington requested additional permits for the docking of
other 19 artillery-armed ships, just in case their assistance is
necessary in the antidrug patrolling.
</P>
<P>
The authorization for those tasks of surveillance and pursuit
of drug traffickers was approved Thursday night in a voting with
36 deputies for and four against.
</P>
<P>
The Costa Rican Legislative Assembly is made up of 57 deputies,
of which 17 were absent of the plenum.
</P>
<P>
The permit is part of an "Agreement of joint antidrug
patrolling" approved in December of 1998 by the Costa Rican
Congress.
</P>
<P>
This is the first agreement struck by Washington with a Central
American country, that authorizes for a 10 year period, that can
be extended, the entrance of U.S. ships and personnel to
jurisdictional territory, waters and skies.
</P>
<P>
United States antidrug police data show that about 350 tons of
cocaine pass through Central American territory toward their
country's drugs consumers market, the biggest of the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
