<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Nailbomb Killer Jailed For Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A young British engineer who
carried out a 13-day reign of terror in London was jailed for life
on Friday for three murders.
</P>
<P>
David Copeland, 24, had admitted causing three explosions in
London, which killed three and injured 129.
</P>
<P>
He had denied murder, admitting manslaughter on the grounds of
diminished responsibility due to paranoid. But he faced a murder
trial after the prosecution refused to accept his plea.
</P>
<P>
The jury of four women and eight men decided he was not
suffering from diminished responsibility at the time of his
attacks, meaning he was guilty of all three murders.
</P>
<P>
Copeland showed no emotion as the verdict was read out in court.
</P>
<P>
"Anyone who has heard the facts of this case will be appalled
and horrified at the atrocity of your crimes," Judge Michael Hyam
said after the sentence.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing can excuse or justify the evil you have done and
certainly not the abhorrent views which you have embraced," he
said.
</P>
<P>
People in and outside the court, including victims injured in
Copeland's bomb attacks, cheered and clapped as the verdict was
read out.
</P>
<P>
Copeland's lawyer, Peter Silver, told reporters after the
verdict that it was unclear how his client was feeling.
</P>
<P>
"It is too early to say if he could recover from his condition,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Silva said his legal team had not yet decided whether to
challenge the conviction, but admitted there were "limited grounds
" for an appeal.
</P>
<P>
Copeland will be sent to a high security hospital to serve six
life sentences for his crimes.
</P>
<P>
The young engineer, who told police he carried out the attacks
because he wanted to start a "racial war", showed no emotion as
the verdict and the sentences were read out.
</P>
<P>
Copeland, who self-confessed that he hero-worshipped Hitler,
targeted London's ethnic and gay communities in April 1999.
</P>
<P>
The crude bombs he built in his bedroom, its walls decked with
Nazi regalia, were packed with nails up to six inches (15
centimeters) long. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine President Calls for Strengthening Mercosur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Fernando
de la Rua called Friday here for surmounting the short-term vision
to achieve a stronger regional bloc.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine president expressed in the speech he delivered
during the Southern Common Market (Mercosur) Presidents Summit the
confidence that the member countries will surmount circumstantial
inconveniences and will advance in the key themes for the full
functioning of the customs union.
</P>
<P>
He said that the strengthening of the bloc's credibility will
contribute to diminishing the regional risks and promoting the
investments that will help reduce unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Efforts must be redoubled to fulfill the commitments made in
the matter of elimination of non-tariff barriers, and to maintain
the full force of the common external tariff, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine president stressed the need of working in the
instruments for the consolidation of "a united, real and genuine
market" and of coordinating the macroeconomic policies to relaunch
Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
De la Rua, Mercosur's rotating president for the first semester
of the year, called for making bigger efforts to continue the
negotiations with the Andean Community with Mexico, with the Free
Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA) and with the European Union to
establish a free trade area.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur is formed by Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay,
with Bolivia and Chile as associate members. The bloc is holding
its 18th summit meeting here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
