<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Proposes L. America To Sign PPI Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The signing of a PPI agreement between Latin American countries
would create the most extensive zone of uniform treatment for
foreign investment "because the field of application would extend
from Mexico to the Tierra del Fuego," according to Banderas.
</P>
<P>
The PPI accord are bilateral agreements signed between states
aimed at creating conditions of security for foreign investors in
the country and for the country's investors abroad.
</P>
<P>
The first PPI agreement was signed between Germany and Pakistan
in 1959. These treaties began to be generalized in the years of
the 1980 decade, so now they have a practically universal
character.
</P>
<P>
There are now more than 1,600 PPI agreements, and 155 countries
are part of bilateral pacts on investments.
</P>
<P>
SELA figures show that Latin America and the Caribbean received
41 percent of direct foreign investment flows to developing
countries in 1998, expecting to increase because of the
privatization of some 140 regional enterprises in the immediate
future, with some 60 billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
