<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Prioritize Technical Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government is to lay
emphasis on technical education to reduce the number of unemployed
college and university graduates in the country, said Education
Minister Tunde Adeniran in Abuja on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The News Agency of Nigeria Friday quoted Adeniran as saying
that the government is worried by the high number of graduates who
remained jobless long after leaving school.
</P>
<P>
"Intake into technical schools will soon be raised," he said,
expressing the hope that the new policy would successfully address
the unemployment problem.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, technological education is also
being promoted in universities across the country to make
graduates more employable after leaving school.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has a number of technical schools, in addition to a
host of polytechnics and universities spread in the 36 states in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Education is one of the priority areas of the present
administration in Nigeria, which has launched the Universal Basic
Education and the Mass Literacy Program to increase the enrolment
of school-age children and to make about 40 million Nigerians
literate in the next eight years.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the focus on education, the minister said there is
need to provide quality education to the citizens to build a
generation of Nigerians who would not be a liability to the
community. 
</P>
