<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Improve Aviation Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has started the deployment
of navigational aids to various airports nationwide in a major
effort to improve aviation safety in the country, the News Agency
of Nigeria reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The state-of-the-art navigational equipments include 19 sets of
 instrument landing system, 10 very high omni-directional radio
ranges, 10 distance measuring equipment and 10 non-directional
beacons, managing director Ibrahim Auyo of the Nigerian Airspace
Management Agency was quoted by the news agency as saying in
Lagos.
</P>
<P>
He said the first set of the equipment had been deployed to
airports in Owerri and Enugu in the southeast, and Zaria, Kaduna
and Ilorin in the north.
</P>
<P>
The airports, serving mostly local flights, had been operating
without functional navigational aids.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government carved out the Nigerian Airspace
Management Agency in 1999 from the Federal Airports Authority of
Nigeria to oversee aviation safety in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Nigeria Civil Aviation Authority was established
as the industry's regulatory body. 
</P>
</TEXT>
