<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lagos Strike Continues, More States Join </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The strike by workers in Nigeria's
commercial capital Lagos to force their state government to raise
minimum wage continued on Friday as workers in more states in the
country also downed tools.
</P>
<P>
Speaking Thursday after abortive talks to resolve the eight-day
strike, Lagos governor Bola Tinubu went tough, saying his
administration would now consider staff rationalization as a way
out of the wage crisis.
</P>
<P>
According to Tinubu, the workers remained adamant in spite of
the fact that the state government had shifted position. The
state's executive council would soon meet to take a decision on
the staff retrenchment option, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government said it would pay 7,500 naira -- the amount
demanded by the workers as monthly minimum wage -- only to senior
workers while junior workers would make do with the 5,500 naira
offered earlier to all the workers by the state (100 naira is
equivalent to one U.S. dollar).
</P>
<P>
The 47,000-strong governmental employee work force is demanding
an across-the-board payment of 7,500 naira before they can call
off the strike, which has paralyzed government activities in the
state, forced state-owned schools to close and crippled health and
other utility services.
</P>
<P>
"That (retrenchment) is a possible option because we cannot
paralyze the business of the state," Tinubu said.
</P>
<P>
The crisis started on May 1 when the federal government
announced a new monthly minimum wage of 7,500 naira for its
workers and 5,500 naira for their counterparts in the 36 states.
</P>
<P>
However, workers in the states demanded between 6,500 and 7,500
naira while most state governors insisted that they could only
manage to pay the stipulated wage.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, workers in Ondo State, also in the southwest, have
decided to join the strike next Monday, saying they would not
accept anything less than 7,500 naira.
</P>
<P>
Workers in most of the other states are continuing negotiations
with their governments, with many of them threatening a strike
like the one in Lagos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
