<HEADLINE> Dominican Banana Producers to Be Affected by EU Preferences Elimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Some 40,000 Dominican Republic
banana producers could be affected by the eventual elimination of
the system of preferential export quotas applied by the European
Union to the members of the Africa, Caribbean, and Pacific (ACP)
countries, said Friday Max Puig, Lome coordinator for the
Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
The European Union is pressured by the United States government
and several banana producing countries not favored by the European
system, to eliminate the banana exports preferential quota system
applied to the ACP group, said Puig, quoted in a press dispatch
from Santo Domingo received here.
</P>
<P>
Puig told the "El Caribe" newspaper that the Dominican Republic
government "has shown a firm attitude" in defense of the more than
40,000 Dominican banana producers.
</P>
<P>
The Dominican Republic exports 60,000 tons of bananas a year to
the European Union, according to a source in the local Lome office.
</P>
<P>
Puig said that the last measures taken by the European Union
about the banana exports have favored the Dominican Republic, but
that the international conflict promoted by a group of U.S. backed
Latin American banana producing countries before the World Trade
Organization (WTO), is a threat for the local producers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
