<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Court Committee Sues to Disbar Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. court committee Friday
sued President Bill Clinton in a bid to disbar him as a lawyer for
denying his sexual contact with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
The Committee on Professional Conduct of the Arkansas Supreme
Court filed suit in Pulaski County Circuit Court, charging that
Clinton's conduct "damages the legal profession and demonstrates a
lack of overall fitness to hold a license to practice law."
</P>
<P>
The committee said that Clinton "has conducted himself in a
manner that violates the model rules of professional conduct as
adopted by the Arkansas Supreme Court."
</P>
<P>
The committee voted on May 19 to sue Clinton over "serious
misconduct" in the Paula Jones sexual harassment case, accusing
him of giving misleading answers about his relationship with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who has 30 days to respond to the lawsuit, has said
that his lawyers would fight the disbarment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time an effort has been made to strip a
sitting president of his law license in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was impeached by the House and acquitted by the Senate
for his sexual scandal. He was also fined 90,000 dollars for
contempt of court by a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, a licensed lawyer since September 7, 1973, was
attorney general of Arkansas from 1977-79, but he has not
practiced law since the early 1980s.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
