<DOCNO> XIE20000630.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Community Calls for Ending Colombian Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Delegates from the countries and
world organizations attending the International Public Audience on
the environment and the illicit cultivation here called Friday for
ending violence in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
The 21 countries participating in the audience and the
representatives of the United Nations and of the European Union in
Colombia agreed to make a forceful call to all the actors in the
violent events to respect human rights an fundamental liberties,
the rules of the Humanitarian International Law and the integrity
of the civilian population, the main victim of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The final statement of the meeting, published Friday, stresses
the significant advances in the process of peace established by
the government and the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (
FARC) and calls on the parts to put an end "to impunity, to
paramilitarism, and to all violent actions, massacres, extortion,
and kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
The signers of the statement called on the Table of Dialogue to
cooperate in the eradication of illicit plants cultivation through
alternative development and to stop drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
 Long civil war in the South American country has caused huge
personal and material damages.
</P>
<P>
 The FARC, which controls about 40 percent of Colombia and is
Latin America's largest and oldest surviving leftist rebel force,
is engaged in a slow-moving peace talks with the government. But
no cease-fire deal has been agreed on as part of the peace process,
which is aimed at ending a conflict that has taken 35,000 lives
over the last decade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
